[{'created': '2014-09-25 07:27:34.000000000', 'message': "Fixes race condition for create default security group

Boot one instance with security_group_api=nova, it will check Nova's
default security group firstly. There is race condition that boot some
instances at the first time for same tenant, current logic is:
1. get default security group
2. if not get it , create one.
Two threads may in step2 , then a exception.SecurityGroupExists is
raised.
Note: this only occurs randomly when boot some instances for same tenant
at the first time.

This commit always tries to create default security group firstly,
then catch the exception SecurityGroupExists.

Closes-Bug: #1373777
Related-Bug: #1303625
Change-Id: I4a311b3697cd7c2e4ac183886d357e057a378baa
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes race condition for create default security group

Boot one instance with security_group_api=nova, it will check Nova's
default security group firstly. There is race condition that boot some
instances at the first time for same tenant, current logic is:
1. get default security group
2. if not get it , create one.
Two threads may in step2 , then a exception.SecurityGroupExists is
raised.
Note: this only occurs randomly when boot some instances for same tenant
at the first time.

This commit always tries to create default security group firstly,
then catch the exception SecurityGroupExists.

Closes-Bug: #1373777
Related-Bug: #1303625
Change-Id: I4a311b3697cd7c2e4ac183886d357e057a378baa

Hi Mehdi,

I have a design question on the first place. The sample in your commit message is not too straight forward IMHO. I'm not the expert of the policy file, so I have more likely a question than a suggestion. Is there a possibility to have a similar structure like we have for pipelines now? So to have the chance to specify list of roles and/or meters, use wildcard, etc.

The mix of the 'or' and 'and' operators and the round brackets seems to be a bit odd to me. And it will be also a bit messy, if we would like to specify the settings for all the meters and several roles. And also a bit odd to me to have the 'access to all meters' and 'all role access this meter' and 'one role access this one meter' options mixed in a line without any explicit mark on it. I know that it is kind of intuitive, as if something is not in between round brackets, then it will apply for all roles/meters, but it will be hard to see the actual configuration with more parameters, I think.

After reading Gordon's BP, I think it could be extended with the aim of this patch. I agree with Nadya and Gordon, it would be good to have a BP for a functionality like this. As the target functionality of this patch and that BP is the same, I mean the restrict access to data based on policy settings, it would be good to synchronize the design anyway, even if it will be a separate BP at the end.

Best Regards,
/Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-04-09 16:51:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Thanks all, for the attention about this patch :), and sorry for my late answer, I have written this to see how the task (writting the ceilometer RBAC system) is complicated.

My personal use case is:

* I want to have some users that only access to cpu and mem related data (for alarming purpose) and the admin/ResellerAdmin user have access to all the data (for some monitoring/audit stuffs). 
* I want to have only one database to record all my openstack samples (so the database have more meters than the alarming user need to have access to).

For very big deployment, we can easily have two separates DB to solve the use case by having one with only the data needed by alarming and an other one with all the data, but for smaller deployment we don't want to duplicate the ceilometer samples into two databases.

About gordc Blueprint (https://blueprints.launchpad.net/ceilometer/+spec/admin-only-api-access), it fits my use case if the way we tracks 'privileged data' take at least of the meter name as criteria.

But does this blueprint aim to filter out some metadatas from a sample/meter/resource, too ?


Alos from the deployer point of view, the policy system is done for this, "design the RBAC/ACL configuration of the component".

This is why I want to use this system and not an other custom ceilometer file to define it.

For this, I have imagined two formats for the policy file:

* 'meter': 'role:admin or meter:cpu or (meter:instance and role:half_powered_user)'

* 'meter_cpu' : '' # everybody
  'meter_instance' : 'role:admin or role:half_powered_user' # admin and role:half_powered_user
  'meter_default' : 'role:admin' \xa0# only admin by default

(@Ildiko: With policy.json you can easily split a rule into multiples rules and having the main rule that calls them to not have a insane long line or to factorize your rules, ex: meter: 'rule:cpu_rule or rule:mem_rule', the default nova policy.json have some examples.)

Also the approach of this patch is to filter out only on the ceilometer-api side the unwanted samples, to not add new param/method on the DB API for now, to avoid complicate our db queries and make the a future V3 API difficult to write.

The patch implements the first policy format, but If we plan to change/enhance the DB API to cover this BP, the seconds one is a better choice because it allows to build the list of allowed/denied meters, the first one doesn't.

But after I have writing this patch, I have seen some blocker issues to solve before writing more code:

* What about user posted samples ? 
  I think the ceilometer-api used to publish samples must set a different 'source' on samples, but currently user are allowed to set the source, so...
* How to filter out resources related to a meter without changing DB API (In the patch I made assumption about the meter_links, but it doesn't work anymore since we can request resource without the meter_links set)
* What about the alarm-evaluator ? 
  @eoghan have already found an issue, when RBAC config change alarm-evaluator can be allow to access to forbidden meters. 
  I see an other one: If an user post a 'mem' sample throught the API, and 'mem' sample that came from openstack are forbidden for the user, how to know a mem sample is allowed or not for this user if we cannot trust the 'source' field of a sample. (Perhaps forbid to set the source ? having a different default source for external samples and internal samples and forbid the internal one)


I hope I have answered to all your questions. Your thoughts are welcome about the blocker issues.'}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-04-23 15:43:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

commit_message:
Filter meter in API according policy

This patch allows to define the permission to access to meters throught
the policy system like this:

   'have_access_to_meter': 'role:admin or meter:cpu or (meter:instance
   and role:half_powered_user)'

This example means:

* role admin have access to data about all meters
* everyone have access to cpu meter related data
* role half_powered_user have access to cpu and instance meter related
  data

If the user is not admin it continues to be scoped to its own data.

Co-Authored-By: Ala Rezmerita <ala.rezmerita@cloudwatt.com>

Change-Id: Ife4fef6d78412a5c9b885fea5060227aa3e4e08e

commit_message:
Add uniq constraint for resource/entity_name

A resource should not have two entities with the same name.

This change adds the uniq contraint to the ResourceEntity.

And it also adds the index of the id key of resources to make mysql
happy...

Change-Id: I08b4bf09448ad49d4c338a1b514589b4f367b052

commit_message:
Allows to append entities to a resource

Currently the only ways to change the entities of a resource is to
replace all the entities with PATCH call on the resource.

This change allows to append new entities to a resource without touching
entities already associated with it.

We also add a uniq constraint for resource/entity_name to enforce the
uniqueness of the entity name on a resource and also add the index of
the id key of resources to make mysql happy...

Change-Id: Ia110a7289483b1c8724ab084dd1a7f1846fa593a

commit_message:
Use basename when setting PS4

The PS4 mangling that devtest.sh does is very useful in showing
exactly where an issue with a devtest run is going wrong. However,
for users that have a TRIPLEO_ROOT set, this turns the PS4 prompt
into a mass of 70 lines, which harms debugging. Use basename to
only show the script itself, rather than the full path.

Change-Id: Ie55e714d50622ac38f36f67a26af5b138c1d2f48

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-03 19:03:35.000000000', 'message': "Fix build + delete races

Nova should always try to unprovision and just fall through if Ironic
tells it that the node is already unprovisioned. Combined with the fact
that nova will retry on 409s, this will resolve any race conditions with
builds and deletes:

An unprovision while Ironic is deploying will result in a 409 HTTP
Conflict. Once the deploy finishes, the unprovision will go through
after nova retries a number of times.

This also does allow concurrent unprovision requests to Ironic, but this is
okay. The 2nd one will 409 because ironic has an outstanding task on the
node and keep retrying until the first one completes. At that point,
nova will get a BadRequest and move on because the node was
already unprovisioned.

Also: We should make the scheduler skip any nodes that have a
provision_state while there's no instance_uuid assigned. This
probably means something bad has happened, so let's treat it as if
the node is in maintenance mode.

Change-Id: I8960dec7c610f7bc5cfcfdbcc1c6b2527c1ca388
Closes-bug: 1337461
"}]
commit_message:
Fix build + delete races

Nova should always try to unprovision and just fall through if Ironic
tells it that the node is already unprovisioned. Combined with the fact
that nova will retry on 409s, this will resolve any race conditions with
builds and deletes:

An unprovision while Ironic is deploying will result in a 409 HTTP
Conflict. Once the deploy finishes, the unprovision will go through
after nova retries a number of times.

This also does allow concurrent unprovision requests to Ironic, but this is
okay. The 2nd one will 409 because ironic has an outstanding task on the
node and keep retrying until the first one completes. At that point,
nova will get a BadRequest and move on because the node was
already unprovisioned.

Also: We should make the scheduler skip any nodes that have a
provision_state while there's no instance_uuid assigned. This
probably means something bad has happened, so let's treat it as if
the node is in maintenance mode.

Change-Id: I8960dec7c610f7bc5cfcfdbcc1c6b2527c1ca388
Closes-bug: 1337461

commit_message:
Drop stack name from the neutron agent-list check

Heat doesn't always include the full name of the stack in in the
resource name (which gets propagated into the neutron agents). The
previous check was failing when the NovaCompute resource was wrapped in
a provider template and/or a ResourceGroup.

Change-Id: I50c72aca9c69545d58a1a6ebd09c189c41c19551

commit_message:
Run the whole test suite as one run

The current approach of running two runs corrupts the testrepository
metadata about the available tests, current failures, and causes
unbounded growth of .testrepository/0 on developer machines. Instead,
use a single run comprising both the Ironic and Nova driver tests.
To do this requires working around the (reasonable) oslo.config
requirement that any option be unique - since both Nova and Ironic
have locally defined options with the same name.

Change-Id: I3f591f1c668c68fc2c8a1ebd51cae8fddefa3d06

commit_message:
Extract stunnel from openstack-ssl

Other elements may wish to use stunnel, so split its installation and
management into a new element which openstack-ssl (and the other
elements) can have in their element-deps.

Change-Id: Ia2cc793448a20244f781666e3ed1889f85e227c5

[{'created': '2014-09-24 09:20:37.000000000', 'message': 'Add test for simple deployment with zabbix

Includes:
* turn on experimental mode
* restart nailgun
* check that new role appears
* deploy cluster
* run ostf
* get zabbix url
* login in dashboard, get events

Add test for simple deployment with zabbix

Includes:
* turn on experimental mode
* restart nailgun
* check that new role appears
* deploy cluster
* run ostf
* get zabbix url
* login in dashboard, get events

[{'created': '2014-09-22 17:11:30.000000000', 'message': 'Use correct WSGI dir on SUSE distros

The current default (/var/www) leads to:

AH01797: client denied by server configuration:
/var/www/keystone/admin

For /var/www the needed permissions on SUSE are not set.
For /srv/www/htdocs/ the permissions are correct on SUSE systems.

Change-Id: I3f2df896daecdfe510d45ff121af2a8433a4d5be
'}]
commit_message:
Use correct WSGI dir on SUSE distros

The current default (/var/www) leads to:

AH01797: client denied by server configuration:
/var/www/keystone/admin

For /var/www the needed permissions on SUSE are not set.
For /srv/www/htdocs/ the permissions are correct on SUSE systems.

Change-Id: I3f2df896daecdfe510d45ff121af2a8433a4d5be

commit_message:
Convert parse error to text type

Some local environments (but not yet the gate) are experiencing
failure of InstantiationDataTest.test_format_parse_invalid_message.

This change fixes that test by converting the parse exception to
a text type before including it in the error message.

Change-Id: I06e271559e27452a7a0c1e8807a37bb5ed5df2fa
Closes-Bug: #1365880

WIP - looking at retaining process_options in service.py'}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-09-23 08:08:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Just wanted to record the reasoning behind process_options() in this comment thread.

process_options() was added in order to allow the SwiftService object to make use of the Openstack auth environment variables in a similar way to the shell code. I believe that the conflicting auth v2/v3 processing crept back in during a rebase onto master. I would prefer to see the code for modifying the keystone options moved to service.py where it can also be used by external projects. I believe that all the exit conditions for enforce_requires in parse_args could be retained by raising a service.SwiftError with an appropriate error message.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-09-23 13:37:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-09-23 13:40:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-09-23 13:53:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Latest patch set leaves option processing in service.py and fixes the bug there, so as not to break other clients.

Have discussed this with Joel and agreed that there is scope for further rationalisation/de-deduplication of the code in shell.parse_args and service.process_options. However, I am reluctant to rush into stripping code out of shell.parse_args() and moving it into service.py without checking through all the subsequent code paths for unforeseen consequences, so for the time being the option processing is duplicated in shell and service, which fixes the immediate bug.

In the longer term I'd like to discuss whether *all* the option mangling is needed in SwiftService - e.g. handling 'old-style' -A -U -K options - or whether SwiftService should expect (and enforce) a 'clean' set of options. In which case shell.py would continue to handle old/new style options - some code would disappear from shell.parse_args and some code would disappear from service.process_opts."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-23 17:43:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix bug with some OS options not being passed to client

Fixes a regression that is preventing swiftclient from
authenticating using keystone v3 options.

swiftclient/shell.py processes the dict of command
line options to set up a child dict ('os_options')
of keystone auth specific options (line 960). The
processing includes stripping --os- prefixes from
the command line options before adding keys to
os_options.

A recent patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/85453/
introduced a duplication of this option processing
in service.py (line 79) which replaces the os_options
created in shell.py, but omits keystone v3 related
options. Consequently the keystone v3 options are
not being passed to the client get_auth() method.

This patch adds the keystone v3 related options to
the option processing in service.py.

For pragmatic reasons (i.e. fixing the bug quickly)
the option processing code has not been removed from
parse_args in shell.py. It is likely that the code in
parse_args is now redundant, but all code paths between
parse_args and process_options should be inspected and
test coverage added before removing that code.

Unit tests have been added in test_shell.py to verify
that command line options are correctly passed to the
client get_auth method.

The MockHttpTest class is re-used in test_shell.py,
so it is moved from test_swiftclient.py
to tests/unit/utils.py

Closes-bug: #1372465

Change-Id: I4fed013cdb8936509609d06093337cc147ade0d6

commit_message:
Fix --heat-env in devtest_overcloud.sh

When a custom heat-env value had been set, the call to Heat still used a
hardcoded path to $TRIPLEO_ROOT/overcloud-env.json.

Change-Id: I5bc7368a567618db5b0c7bb88eafea6093b73b21

db archive_deleted_rows consistent

Use higher row count than the number of server
expected to created in a tempest run.

It would make the test results more consistent.

Related-Bug: #1305892

commit_message:
labs: simplify waiting for namespaces

This patch simplifies the loop used to wait for the namespaces to
appear. It makes the code errexit-clean. The names of the namespaces are
still written to the log file.

Change-Id: Ida4a4e7d5a3d8fd002b5201a5201dba22d17fdc0

commit_message:
Fixed up row table printing by giving column names

Previously, a row was printed out in a single column, i.e.
by converting the Python list to a string.

This change ensures that each column is printed individually.
For now this means auto-generating column names.  Once there's
an API call for grabbing a datasource schema, we will change
the datasource column names to meaningful strings.

Change-Id: I1c0f0c429a75284250ec28211504620e9eec05ad

commit_message:
Added missing API end points to the client

This change adds the following commands, which were
not previously present.
    $ openstack congress datasource list
    $ openstack congress datasource rows list
    $ openstack congress datasource rows list --trace
    $ openstack congress datasource tables list
    $ openstack congress policy tables list

Closes-bug: 1368334
Change-Id: Ic4ea722a5fb31eb43dc7af4bde0cd28bbc8f47a1

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Add OmniGraffle file with image source

I tried exporting to SVG but due to the imported icons I used,
  it is not a clean SVG but depends on external PDF files. Rather
  than dirtying up this image directory I'm adding this source
  in case someone can figure out how to properly exoprt to SVG.

Change-Id: I59ebd16e8dab86445d0a789e3a04f253babf64a3

commit_message:
Don't spawn metadata-proxy for non-isolated nets

If the configuation option "enable_isolated_metadata = True" for the
DHCP agent is set, the neutron-ns-metadata-proxy process is spawned
for all networks, regardless if they are isolated or not. In case
the network is not isolated (ie. connected to a neutron router), the
L3 agent also spawns a proxy process, and the DHCP's proxy is left
unused. This patch adds a check prior to the spawning of new proxies:
if a network is not isolated, no proxy is spawned.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/test_dhcp_agent.py

Change-Id: I9bdb8c3d37997b22435bca33ec47a67db08efa51
Closes-bug: #1361545
(cherry picked from commit 9569b2fe58d0e836071992f545886ca985d5ace8)

commit_message:
Add an optional advanced pool of memcached clients

This patchset adds an advanced eventlet safe pool of memcache clients. This
allows the deployer to configure auth_token middleware to utilize the new
pool by simply setting 'memcache_use_advanced_pool' to true. Optional
tunables for the memcache pool have also been added.

Co-Authored-By: Morgan Fainberg <morgan.fainberg@gmail.com>
Closes-bug: #1332058
Closes-bug: #1360446
Change-Id: I08082b46ce692cf4df449d48dac94718f1e98a6c

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Change flavor-manage alias for v3 API

Currently v3 API has alias flavor-manage while v2 has
os-flavor-manage, this patch changes the v3 alias to be same
as v2.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I94b28c274cbf7c5f504aca6c1f9fd12d2159f7a4

commit_message:
Creates a router if one doesn't exist

If it doesn't find a router by the name specified in router_name
in murano.conf, create a router with that name. Uses
external_network_id or external_network_name as the
external_gateway_info ID. Requires:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119800

Change-Id: If8b966a7d43eb2af485113de2a0708e554605725

commit_message:
Use only specific router for created networks

Murano should not use first available router it may create
different networking issues cause router may not have access to
external network.

Closes-bug: #1366124
Change-Id: I223a4862c3b20cfb20281be6bd9376be3644ad92

commit_message:
Install debootstrap in debian element

Building debian images using dib is complaining when debootstrap
package is missing. Added an element to properly install it
to ensure element is working in all cases

Change-Id: I4be526bcb6357e688c22d947e90858a0b2fb94b1

Hello Ben,

I'd like to reply your points:

>>> Trying to maintain those while also having an automated version is just going to lead to inconsistency and confusion IMHO.

Agreed, so in PS#2 I have not checked automated version (glance.sample.conf) in, and just remained split configs. So there is no inconsistency on the configs within the trunk.

>>> I don't know that the config generator can handle split configs, but if that's a blocker to switching Glance entirely to use it, please open a bug with Oslo so we can look into how to handle that. Thanks.

I also like to see the automated version could replaces those manual version (even we could use script to generate it as needed and remove all templates from repo), but I think we concerned now on what you said here: config generator couldn't handle split configs.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2014-04-01 02:25:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

[{'created': '2014-03-27 09:42:09.000000000', 'message': 'Enabling sample configuration file generation for Glance

As a common approach most projects used now and Oslo preferred, this
change enabled sample configuration file generation mechanism for
Glance.

The changes including:
1. Added config.generator from Oslo-inc.
2. Added config tools: generate_sample.sh and check_uptodate.sh .
3. Made "pep8" checking of tox (-epep8) and run_tests.sh (-p) to involve
sample configuration file updated-checking.
4. Added "genconfig" function as a tox testenv (-egenconfig). Developer
or milestone maintainer could use it to obtain Glance configuration
template as needed.
5. Unified all configuration files path and merge to single:
etc/glance/glance.conf.sample .

The benefits:
1. Don't need to upgrade configuration template file manually, and no
worry on configuration template file out-of-date.
2. Provied a way to allow developer or milestone maintainer to obtain
Glance configuration template easily.
3. pep8 check will cover configuration template file as well, to prevent
it out-of-date.
4. Using single template file instead of separated ones. It could
prevent duplicated code and changes, and to reduce maintenance effort.

Change-Id: I94d486d6686815c45705a7a9b00fb26062e1eb63
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>'}, {'created': '2014-03-28 08:05:39.000000000', 'message': 'Enabling sample configuration file generation for Glance

As a common approach most projects used now and Oslo preferred, this
change enabled sample configuration file generation mechanism for
each Glance services.

This change, as an enhancement, allows generating separated sample
configuration files for each Glance major services, e.g.:

    etc/glance-api.conf.sample
    etc/glance-cache.conf.sample
    etc/glance-manage.conf.sample
    etc/glance-registry.conf.sample
    etc/glance-scrubber.conf.sample

It is different than I94d486d6686815c45705a7a9b00fb26062e1eb63
which only supports generating an unified sample configuration
file to including all Glance available options.

This mechanism  not only can help auditing by packager, milestone
maintainer or developer as a function (testenv) of tox, but also
those separated configuration files could make deployment be easy.
And it helps keeping sample configuration files be update with
code change.

The change added "genconfigs" function as a tox testenv (-egenconfigs),
and it dependes on oslo-config-generator function of oslo.config.

The change doesn't introduce those sample files Glance repo, so
next step is to investigate if we can generate them in gate
automatically when a change was merged.

commit_message:
Enabling sample configuration file generation for Glance

As a common approach most projects used now and Oslo preferred, this
change enabled sample configuration file generation mechanism for
Glance.

This mechanism can help auditing by packager, milestone maintainer or
developer as a function (testenv) of tox. The change doesn't introduce
glance.sample.conf into Glance repo but keep separated service
configuration files instead, this could make deployment be easy.

The changes including:
1. Added config.generator from Oslo-inc.
2. Added config tools: generate_sample.sh and check_uptodate.sh .
3. Added "genconfig" function as a tox testenv (-egenconfig). Packager,
milestone maintainer or developer might use it to obtain Glance
configuration template as needed.

Change-Id: I94d486d6686815c45705a7a9b00fb26062e1eb63
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Add TRIPLEO_DEBUG var for enabling debug logging

If we would like to run any jobs with debug logging enabled (which we
would like to for the HA job) then we need a way for to specify this.

Depends on tripleo-incubator change:
I3f267f3d6290fddb40d80b1c889bade8980ddb43

Change-Id: Icf36094605eeaf6923ea1a9ab60386eda11730e9

commit_message:
Revert "Datepicker locale support"

This commit broke all tripleo ci jobs, DATEPICKER_LOCALE doesn't appear
to be getting set in _scripts.html.
This reverts commit 78c917570e2182bfdd8f5cb7eb5cb2c71d8df6f0.
Related-Bug: #120242

Change-Id: Ie03558e15890c779d30119834a6def4a00fd4784

commit_message:
Neutron: Atomic update of instance info cache

In the Neutron network API implementation, there is a race condition
between a thread performing periodic task to read and heal instance
network info cache and another thread servicing interface-attach or
interface-detach calls. This patch ensures that instance info cache is
read and then updated in a synchronized block to ensure atomicity.

Please see the bug report for more details.

Change-Id: Ifc76f2b1cce834b3c9927359ac9b957bc9f9c65f
Closes-Bug: #1326183
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>

I'll try to take a closer look at some point and give you better help…)"}, {'account_id': 12869, 'date': '2014-09-24 09:28:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi kevin,

I gone through the code and found the solution that in icmp protocol if we are using -1 port then it is a valid port not a invalid port 
(In nova.network.security_group.security_group_base the check conditions are given for tcp, udp, icmp protocol where we can see that for icmp -1 to 255 are valid port).
We are not able to add invalid rule, only valid rule are accepted to be add. So, accordingly for these scenarios (invalid rules) we need not write test cases.'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2014-09-24 15:11:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm sorry, I don't understand.  Are you saying that the bug that this review is supposedly closing is actually invalid, and so this is not needed?  If so, you should abandon it."}, {'account_id': 12869, 'date': '2014-09-25 06:07:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
no obvious way to delete incorrect security rule

Previously deleting incorrect/invalid security
group rule was throwing the error of
"AttributeError". With this fix, now the
invalid security group rules can be deleted.

Change-Id: Ia6e9d2a0d23554ac9ab6ccd8a077714db9ae82a0
closes-bug: 1163469

commit_message:
Fix NoopQuotasDriver.get_settable_quotas()

get_settable_quotas() always failed with KeyError. While this driver
is not really useful, we still want it to be working.

Closes-Bug: #1363014

Change-Id: Ia6986453338cee05f28ff081c6bb1279072c3d80

[{'created': '2014-09-04 16:43:44.000000000', 'message': "VMware: Remove host argument to ds_util.get_datastore()

Since the removal of the ESX driver, we no longer pass host to
ds_util.get_datastore(), and we always pass a cluster. This change
removes the host argument, and assumes we always get a cluster.

This is a relatively simple change, but it has 2 knock-on effects to
tests. Firstly, almost all tests using get_datastore were passing host
and cluster as None, None, which excercised a code path which only
made a single vim call. This meant that passing in
fake.FakeObjectRetrievalSession() worked well. That code path was
removed (because it was never actually called), and the new code path
makes either 2 or 3 vim calls. This requires more complex faking of
vim calls, which we do in _mock_get_datastore_calls(). Note that this
is only faking the vim calls, so we're still testing get_datastore,
not the fake function.

The second knock-on effect is to the incredibly fragile
test_spawn_mask_block_device_info_password in test_vmops. This test
has to allow enough of spawn() to run to generate a debug log message,
as it is testing that log message. This change caused an irrelevant
exception to be raised in _get_vm_config_info, which prevented it
getting as far as the log message. We poke the test a bit so it
doesn't break any more.

Finally, we entirely remove test_get_datastore_no_host_in_cluster
because:

1. the previous code did 'if datastore_ret:' so returning '' and None,
   as returned by test_get_datastore_without_datastore, were
   previously functionally identical. Incidentally, this change also
   fixes that.
2. its purpose wasn't clear anyway.

Change-Id: I37f1ea126ae2e7f86cfd29d399fba1c527f18dc0

commit_message:
VMware: Remove host argument to ds_util.get_datastore()

Since the removal of the ESX driver, we no longer pass host to
ds_util.get_datastore(), and we always pass a cluster. This change
removes the host argument, and assumes we always get a cluster.

This is a relatively simple change, but it has 2 knock-on effects to
tests. Firstly, almost all tests using get_datastore were passing host
and cluster as None, None, which excercised a code path which only
made a single vim call. This meant that passing in
fake.FakeObjectRetrievalSession() worked well. That code path was
removed (because it was never actually called), and the new code path
makes either 2 or 3 vim calls. This requires more complex faking of
vim calls, which we do in _mock_get_datastore_calls(). Note that this
is only faking the vim calls, so we're still testing get_datastore,
not the fake function.

The second knock-on effect is to the incredibly fragile
test_spawn_mask_block_device_info_password in test_vmops. This test
has to allow enough of spawn() to run to generate a debug log message,
as it is testing that log message. This change caused an irrelevant
exception to be raised in _get_vm_config_info, which prevented it
getting as far as the log message. We poke the test a bit so it
doesn't break any more.

Finally, we entirely remove test_get_datastore_no_host_in_cluster
because:

1. the previous code did 'if datastore_ret:' so returning '' and None,
   as returned by test_get_datastore_without_datastore, were
   previously functionally identical. Incidentally, this change also
   fixes that.
2. its purpose wasn't clear anyway.

Change-Id: I37f1ea126ae2e7f86cfd29d399fba1c527f18dc0

[{'created': '2014-09-23 22:46:32.000000000', 'message': 'Reduce the log level for the guestfs being missing.

There are platforms where we can never reasonably expect libguestfs
to be functional (FreeBSD, libvirt / lxc, etc). Reduce the log
level of the message recording that libguestfs is unavailable to
reduce operator confusion.

As discussed on openstack-dev at:

  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/046910.html

Change-Id: I4bd7ed4fbffb8ac22aea4285fe74ee0d78e1581c
'}]
commit_message:
Reduce the log level for the guestfs being missing.

There are platforms where we can never reasonably expect libguestfs
to be functional (FreeBSD, libvirt / lxc, etc). Reduce the log
level of the message recording that libguestfs is unavailable to
reduce operator confusion.

As discussed on openstack-dev at:

  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/046910.html

Change-Id: I4bd7ed4fbffb8ac22aea4285fe74ee0d78e1581c

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-12 01:18:00.000000000', 'message': "Set LDAP certificate trust options for LDAPS and TLS

We currently only set the LDAP library certificate trust options
when TLS is being used (via startTLS).  If regular LDAPS is being

commit_message:
Set LDAP certificate trust options for LDAPS and TLS

We currently only set the LDAP library certificate trust options
when TLS is being used (via startTLS).  If regular LDAPS is being
used, the certificate trust options that are defined in Keystone's
configuration file are never actually set.

This patch sets the certificate trust options for both LDAPS and
TLS cases.

Conflicts:
        keystone/common/ldap/core.py
        keystone/tests/unit/common/test_ldap.py

Closes-bug: #1209343
Change-Id: Ieb94b732f623695920feb34995bb863175ddf27a
(cherry picked from commit ca50b6315909faf92db9eaf2981782bcd80cfab8)

commit_message:
fix statistics query in postgres

when aggregate functions present, postgres requires all
non-aggregate columns selected to be included in group by clause
to ensure a single value is selected.

Change-Id: Iccbcd8046cca872e8eba472f48fa392114f34426
Closes-Bug: #1256318
(cherry picked from commit 551bbbb0dff43d22d7cca7826af1b3ef5868168b)

[{'created': '2014-09-23 23:43:39.000000000', 'message': "Prevent infinite recursion on persistence core on init

Raise an AttributeError for lookup on 'token_provider_api' within the
__getattr__ on the keystone.token.persistence.core.Manager class. The
__getattr__ will be called on dependency injection process dependencies
and attempt to do a lookup on .token_provider_api, which nets an
infinite recursion. If an AttributeError is raised the dependency
processor will set the value correctly. Once the 'token_provider_api'
attribute is set, __getattr__ is no longer called as the value is in
the instantiated object's __dict__.

Change-Id: I4af79f4568429dea27c1e11e5a77cefa5afc792c
Closes-Bug: #1373167

commit_message:
Prevent infinite recursion on persistence core on init

Raise an AttributeError for lookup on 'token_provider_api' within the
__getattr__ on the keystone.token.persistence.core.Manager class. The
__getattr__ will be called on dependency injection process dependencies
and attempt to do a lookup on .token_provider_api, which nets an
infinite recursion. If an AttributeError is raised the dependency
processor will set the value correctly. Once the 'token_provider_api'
attribute is set, __getattr__ is no longer called as the value is in
the instantiated object's __dict__.

Change-Id: I4af79f4568429dea27c1e11e5a77cefa5afc792c
Closes-Bug: #1373167

client by interface.
2. Corrected swift driver to involve options from swift driver utils,
allow glance_store exports and registers them for client.
3. Added missing test cases for the functions of swift driver util.
4. Using unicode() on exception object for logging to prevent potential
encoding issue, btw.
5. Removed a useless function _delete_image_from_backend(), btw.

commit_message:
Enhance configuration handling

1. Changed drivers to prevent using global CONF but access it from
client by interface.
2. Corrected swift driver to involve options from swift driver utils,
allow glance_store exports and registers them for client.
3. Added missing test cases for the functions of swift driver util.

Change-Id: I8fac6800efde202e29179791ea05c4814ec58435
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

I'm ok with the test setUp refactoring into a mix-in and splitting the the new account auditor tests into separate pre/post-migration test cases.  The assertUnMigrated helper seems like a tasteful method extraction.  I'm less convinced that self.broker will scale out if we need to add a test method that exercises multiple account db's - but we can jump that bridge when we come to it.

FWIW, I came up with the old_broker context manager thing when working on storage policies cause it was really useful to grab the legacy schema patchers in non-unittesting situations (e.g. manual functional tests, probetests, micro-benchmark scripts) and generally only needed the Broker patched long enough to get the schema on disk.  That experience is why I copied the pattern here.  But it's demonstrably trivial to wrap the classes setup/teardown into a context manager if/when I find myself needing that again, and it's definitely a more familiar pattern to use setUp/tearDown base-classes in unittests.  Sorry if it was ascetically distasteful to proliferate the use of those convenience classmethods.

Thanks darrell!"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-24 00:16:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add container_count to policy_stat table

Start tracking the container count per policy including reporting
it in account HEAD and supporting installations where the DB
existed before the updated schema.

Migration is triggered by the account audtior; if the database is
un-migrated it will continue to report policy_stats without the per
policy container_count keys.

Closes-Bug: #1367514
Change-Id: I07331cea177e19b3df303609a4ac510765a19162

commit_message:
Fixes server list filtering on metadata

In order to specify filtering of returned servers based on
metadata or system metadata a key/value pair string is passed to
the API. However, the string is never converted to a separate
key/value dictionary. This results in the db failing to filter
correctly and causes a stack trace.

This change correctly converts the string values for system
metadata and metadata to dictionaries and fixes the compute api
unittests which previously erroneously assumed that the compute
api layer would be passed search opts in dict format when
required.

Change-Id: I886d5e770fe16fc2194b33c563a131b550f13f59
Closes-Bug: 1372218

commit_message:
Return vcpu pin set as set rather than list

The current implementation of the libvirt driver makes mixed assumptions
about the vcpu pin set returned from hardware.get_vcpu_pin_set(). Most
places in the code assume its a set and perform set operations on the
structure. However a few  places assume it's a list. Given the mixed
assumptions about the structure type, the existing code was trying
to perform set operations on a list.

This patch changes the get_vcpu_pin_set() method to return a set
rather than a list and handles any edge cases where consumers need
a list. It also updates any relevant unit tests accordingly.

Change-Id: I66d5cbc0e2d370d9d2d2ab2bad2c5b348bedba6c
Closes-Bug: 1372829

[{'created': '2014-09-24 15:33:44.000000000', 'message': 'provide sane cmd exit reporting

Previously the debug messages around command exit were a naked return
code with no reference to what was run. When dealing with very long
running commands (especially those that fail) this means that figuring
out what command was run is possibly very difficult.

Change-Id: I6c44e1106f77fab517fcb0b6d6dd8ed56c853496
'}]
commit_message:
provide sane cmd exit reporting

Previously the debug messages around command exit were a naked return
code with no reference to what was run. When dealing with very long
running commands (especially those that fail) this means that figuring
out what command was run is possibly very difficult.

Change-Id: I6c44e1106f77fab517fcb0b6d6dd8ed56c853496

commit_message:
Return None from get_swap() if input is not swap

If a non-swap parameter is passed to get_swap(), return None,
rather than returning the parameter itself.

Change-Id: Icfb0eb0e4d721522160d0b7a4fd9b98c1871a10a
Closes-bug: #1214406

commit_message:
Fix the ordering of assertEqual arguments

This keeps testtools happy, since it expects the argument ordering to be
(expected, actual).

Change-Id: I95b41ad7645700ce23b46c7a5700e79008ed08be
Closes-bug: #1277104

In default security group, if we create a port with IPv4 address, then
delete the IPv6 ingress rule, the neutron server will happen KeyError,
this is because IPv4 and IPv6 have same remote group id, but it should
be solved separately in ipset set.

'}, {'created': '2014-09-24 03:54:08.000000000', 'message': 'Repair errors when l2 agent use enhanced-security-group-rpc

this patch repair two problems:
1. in default security group, if we create a port with IPv4 address, then
delete the IPv4 ingress rule, the neutron server will happen KeyError,
this is because IPv4 and IPv6 have same remote group id, but it should
be solved separately in ipset set.

2. in the case above, if l2 agent enable ipset, iptables-restore will
fail.

ingress rule, then launches an instance in this security group, neutron

commit_message:
Fix KeyError when getting secgroup info for ports

The patch fixes a regression introduced with secgroup rpc refactor by
handling the case when security group contains rules for only IPv4 or
IPv6.

Change-Id: I02b174757bfc796a81cdb482c55ba7f9e954131d
Closes-bug: #1372337

commit_message:
Change compute agent recurring logs from INFO to DEBUG

Repeatedly logging all the data about each instance is too verbose
for the INFO level, it should use the DEBUG level.

Change-Id: I5420c74e364790b2ff0a875337d5cd4d002ab5b5
Closes-Bug: #1373427

It's quite difficult to debug unit test failures when you don't have
any idea when the log messages happened relative to each other. Update

log messages.

Change-Id: I704792f10d77345246d528bd9abf2e0c46b6df72
"}]
commit_message:
add time to logging in unit tests

It's quite difficult to debug unit test failures when you don't have
any idea when the log messages happened relative to each other. Update
the logging fixture so that we are actually writing out time into our
log messages.

Change-Id: I704792f10d77345246d528bd9abf2e0c46b6df72

commit_message:
XenAPI: clean up old snapshots before create new

Before taking a new snapshot, we now inspect the VDI chain to check for
old snapshots.

Those old snapshots can be left behind from resize, migrates, and
snapshots that get interrupted if you kill the nova-compute process.

If you leave these snapshots behind, the hypervisor disk will get too
full, as VDI chains grow much bigger than you would expect. In addition
snapshots start to grow in size, causing issues copying the snapshot
into storage.

Closes-Bug: #1371072

commit_message:
Fix bug in atomic actions

Some code cleanup for the recently merged https://review.openstack.org/111977

We took the atomic actions list by mistake always from the first iteration;
we should continue taking this list from the first non-failed iteration.
Add functional testing for this case.

We also fix the missing "%" sign in the output CLI table in case there were
no successful atomic action iterations.

Co-authored-by: Oleg Anufriev <oanufriev@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Id4095122be8dd8bffeeaeabe407ff76c0f294686
Closes-Bug: 1372739
Closes-Bug: 1372998
Closes-Bug: 1373488
Closes-Bug: 1373576

commit_message:
Removed unused abc meta class

AlarmEvaluationService is not using abc.ABCMeta, so remove it.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-28 17:41:39.000000000', 'message': 'Reject overly-taxing ranged-GET requests

RFC 7233 says that servers MAY reject certain classes of ranged GET
requests. In particular, servers may reject ranged GET requests with
more than two overlapping ranges *or* many non-increasing ranges.

Such requests are fairly hard for Swift to process. Consider a Range
header that asks for the first byte of every 10th MiB in a 4 GiB
object, but in some random order. That'll cause a lot of seeks on the
object server, but the corresponding response body is quite small in
comparison to the workload.

This commit makes Swift reject, with a 416 response, any ranged GET
request with more than two overlapping ranges or with more than 7
("many") non-increasing ranges.

This is a necessary prerequisite for supporting multi-range GETs on
large objects. Otherwise, a malicious user could construct a Range
header with hundreds of byte ranges where each individual byterange
requires the proxy to contact a different object server. If seeking
all over a disk is bad, connecting all over the cluster is way worse.

Change-Id: I4dcedcaae6c3deada06a0223479e611094d57234
'}, {'created': '2014-09-17 22:48:33.000000000', 'message': "Reject overly-taxing ranged-GET requests

RFC 7233 says that servers MAY reject egregious range-GET requests
such as requests with hundreds of ranges, requests with non-ascending
ranges, and so on.

Such requests are fairly hard for Swift to process. Consider a Range
header that asks for the first byte of every 10th MiB in a 4 GiB
object, but in some random order. That'll cause a lot of seeks on the
object server, but the corresponding response body is quite small in
comparison to the workload.

This commit makes Swift reject, with a 416 response, any ranged GET
request with more than fifty ranges, more than three overlapping
ranges, or more than eight non-increasing ranges.

This is a necessary prerequisite for supporting multi-range GETs on
large objects. Otherwise, a malicious user could construct a Range
header with hundreds of byte ranges where each individual byterange
requires the proxy to contact a different object server. If seeking
all over a disk is bad, connecting all over the cluster is way worse.

Change-Id: I4dcedcaae6c3deada06a0223479e611094d57234

commit_message:
Reject overly-taxing ranged-GET requests

RFC 7233 says that servers MAY reject egregious range-GET requests
such as requests with hundreds of ranges, requests with non-ascending
ranges, and so on.

Such requests are fairly hard for Swift to process. Consider a Range
header that asks for the first byte of every 10th MiB in a 4 GiB
object, but in some random order. That'll cause a lot of seeks on the
object server, but the corresponding response body is quite small in
comparison to the workload.

This commit makes Swift reject, with a 416 response, any ranged GET
request with more than fifty ranges, more than three overlapping
ranges, or more than eight non-increasing ranges.

This is a necessary prerequisite for supporting multi-range GETs on
large objects. Otherwise, a malicious user could construct a Range
header with hundreds of byte ranges where each individual byterange
requires the proxy to contact a different object server. If seeking
all over a disk is bad, connecting all over the cluster is way worse.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I4dcedcaae6c3deada06a0223479e611094d57234

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-30 17:33:07.000000000', 'message': "Add additional attributes to choices in ChoiceField

This feature enables user to customize choices in a  drop down
list of a form by adding additional properties to the 'choices'
attribute of ChoiceField class.

Currently, the ChoiceField class has an attribute choices which
takes a list of 2 element tuple by default.

    self.field[<field name>].choices = ([
                                   (option_value1, option_label1),
                                   (option_value2, option_label2)
                                       ])

With this implementation, an additional and optional
attribute/property can be added to the 'choices' attribute of
ChoiceField to add properties specific to each choice.This
additional property will be a dictionary containing any global
html attribute and their values. For example, to define a help
text for each choice:

     self.field[<field name>].choices = ([
           (option_value1, option_label1, {'title': 'help text 1'}),
           (option_value2, option_label2, {'title': 'help text 2'})
          ])

The forms.fields.SelectWidget has been modified to enable this
feature of adding additional properties to the choices attribute
in the ChoiceField class.

Implements: blueprint add-attributes-to-form-field-choices

Change-Id: I8ba997c58b485a33676cf9f350be00a1f365256f

commit_message:
Add additional attributes to choices in ChoiceField

This feature enables user to customize choices in a  drop down
list of a form by adding additional properties to the 'choices'
attribute of ChoiceField class.
Currently, the ChoiceField class has an attribute choices which
takes a list of 2 element tuple by default.
    self.field[<field name>].choices = ([
                                   (option_value1, option_label1),
                                   (option_value2, option_label2)
                                       ])
With this implementation,users can specify an additional transform
function in the forms.fields.SelectWidget class called
transform_html_attrs. Given the option label for a given choice,
transform_html_attrs will return a dictionary containing the html
attributes and their values

Implements: blueprint add-attributes-to-form-field-choices
Change-Id: I8ba997c58b485a33676cf9f350be00a1f365256f

commit_message:
Upgrade django-pyscss to 1.0.3 for Horizon

The version we have now, 1.0.2, has a bug that prevents us from
unbundling the bootstrap 3 files with xstatic. This bug has just
been fixed upstream, and a new version, 1.0.3 is available with
the fix.

Change-Id: Ie70bd8ac0543e138b6a76c10732c7dc98ae63ce8
Closes-bug: 1369514

commit_message:
List servers compute API V2 server status cleanup.

Server status need to be updated to reflect current standards.
Adding statuses like STOPPED, PAUSED, SOFT_DELETED and updating
old values to new ones like RESCUED, RESIZED, DELETED.

Closes-Bug: #1245881

Change-Id: Ib55ef13a0422ffe82a25bc186353c290e04b40c4

commit_message:
Migrate test_load_balancer_basic to tempest client

This patch migrates the load balancer basic ops scenario test from official
client to tempest clients.

It also removes the NeutronRetriever class from the test script

Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

Change-Id: I4f3da202646821671d0e98707031a49973c256b2

commit_message:
Fixed typos in the QOS Spec forms in Volume Types

Under Admin->Volumes->Volume Types, when we click the 'Create QOS
Spec' button, the Description section mentions 'Manage' instead
of 'Manage Specs'.

Change-Id: Ide4691a79539f2cbf3f94d6f16887eb886f8e23d
Closes-Bug: #1371249

Please help.  I cannot figure out how to get the keystone_wsgi_apache tests to pass.  If I do
'include ::apache'
or
'class { apache: purge_configs => false }'
in the pre_condition, I get the errors telling me Duplicate declaration: Class[Apache] is already declared

If I do not have the include apache, the test tells me
Puppet::Error:
2014-07-26 02:53:46.182 |        Failed to parse template apache/mod/ssl.conf.erb:

Please help"}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2014-07-26 21:13:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Hi Richard,

It is in fact a genuine error. A Puppet class cannot be included twice (unless the include syntax is used everywhere). So you cannot include the apache class twice, once with class { '::apache': } and a second with include ::apache.

It is in fact a very known and annoying behaviour in Puppet. To make the test pass, you have to remove include ::apache from the precondition.

This however means that a end user cannot include ::apache elsewhere and include keystone::wsgi::apache without failing the catalog compilation as seen in the test report.

IMO, we should consider this test failure as a warning. What I mean is that our users will most likely encounter this problem in production too. So we should come up with a better way to fix this bug which does not involve including a parameterized apache class."}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2014-08-04 17:48:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

What if I use 

class { '::apache': purge_configs => true}

in the pre-condition?  Then can I use

class { '::apache': purge_configs => false}

in keystone::wsgi::apache?"}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2014-08-04 17:50:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Also note that the current code works fine on Fedora 20 using packstack to install - if packstack has been patched to do the

include ::apache

in the packstack keystone.pp.  So in a "real" puppet run with packstack, it is ok to have

include ::apache

followed by

class { '::apache': purge_configs => false }'}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2014-08-06 21:36:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Ok, I think I understand.  As part of my patch, I included the ability to "call" ::keystone::wsgi::apache from ::keystone.  I need to do the same to spec/classes/keystone_spec.rb - it needs to test using "use_wsgi" and it needs to test everything that keystone_wsgi_apache_spec.rb tests.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-08 17:54:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
setup keystone using apache mod_wsgi

Allow keystone to be set up to use apache mod_wsgi as the server
instead of a standalone eventlet service.  There is a new keystone
class parameter: service_name.  The default is 'keystone', which will
set up the standalone eventlet service.  If 'httpd' is used, the
keystone class will skip creating the keystone service, which also means
no 'openstack-keystone' service.  The class 'keystone::wsgi::apache' is
then used to configure apache mod_wsgi to serve keystone.

Had to remove the File resource default in the keystone class.  When
using wsgi::apache, the apache class and other classes are included.
Since puppet uses dynamic scoping, this overrides the file resources
in those classes as well.  keystone now explicitly sets all of the
parameters in files/directory resources.

Change-Id: Ib05ac81381e169845b44b2ef7cb810a4d5db17de
Closes-Bug: #1348728

patch updates references to use keystonemiddleware instead.

[{'created': '2014-07-02 09:44:12.000000000', 'message': 'Check Apache version in Horizon config

In Apache 2.2, access control is done by the directives such
as allow, deny.  Apache 2.4 now uses mod_authz_host for it.

This change makes horizon.config to check Apache version and
to deal with different configurations by using <IfVersion>
Directive.
This replaces the previous fixes that check Apache or distro
version at the horizon.conf creation time.

Change-Id: I6478db385fda2fa1c75ced12d3e886b2e1152852
'}, {'created': '2014-09-08 05:14:35.000000000', 'message': "Use mod_version to clean-up apache version matching

within devstack scripts.

Clean up the horizon and keystone config file generation to use the
internal apache matching.

'functions' is actually duplicated.  just leave get_apache_version in
lib/apache as it is used for config-file name matching in there.

commit_message:
Use mod_version to clean-up apache version matching

This change uses mod_version (shipped by default on everything we care
about) to set-up version-specific config within apache rather than
within devstack scripts.

Clean up the horizon and keystone config file generation to use the
internal apache matching.

Since I6478db385fda2fa1c75ced12d3e886b2e1152852 the apache matching in
'functions' is actually duplicated.  just leave get_apache_version in
lib/apache as it is used for config-file name matching in there.

commit_message:
Do not return 'id' in REST API error messages

REST API should return 'uuid' instead of 'id' in error messages.

Closes-Bug: #1372499
Change-Id: I0b5c8fce3e50da2a9fa42f6407409dcf6332fa45

commit_message:
Adds vcpus and memory parameters

Adds vcpus and memory parameters to the wait_for_hypervisor_stats
script. Not all nodes will have identical hardware characteristics,
especially in a baremetal environment, so this script needs to be a bit
more flexible. Will follow up with a subsequent patch that makes use of
this functionality in devtest.

Maintains backwards compatibility.

Change-Id: I43d72cc0d2c1ded70af28d9861aa6e28838795bf

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-23 19:11:05.000000000', 'message': "pki-setup should be run regardless of token provider

The puppet-keystone module currently will only execute
'keystone-manage pki_setup' to create the signing key if the PKI
token provider is being used. The signing key/cert is still used
for signing the token revocation list, even when the UUID token
provider is being used. We should be running
'keystone-manage pki_setup' if enable_pki_setup=true, regardless
of token provider.

Change-Id: I2817fbde74cbd50cae31f681503816e576cc7b60
Closes-bug: #1373064
"}]
commit_message:
pki-setup should be run regardless of token provider

The puppet-keystone module currently will only execute
'keystone-manage pki_setup' to create the signing key if the PKI
token provider is being used. The signing key/cert is still used
for signing the token revocation list, even when the UUID token
provider is being used. We should be running
'keystone-manage pki_setup' if enable_pki_setup=true, regardless
of token provider.

Change-Id: I2817fbde74cbd50cae31f681503816e576cc7b60
Closes-bug: #1373064

commit_message:
Add syslog support for Ceph

Ceph now supports syslog facility and
log level features, so it should now be
included in Fuel.

blueprint add-all-openstack-logs-to-ui

Change-Id: I2b039ff724ff88b510c78379b955b3c44eba7f61

commit_message:
Fix formatting of /etc/issue \w different ip sizes

Pointed out by Artem Panchenko that if the ip sizes
are different it will result in ugly formatting.

This is follow up of bug #1351937 and previous patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113605/

Change-Id: I08ce905f8386fe121c8dc9c4963601b674fccf61

commit_message:
Drop autoscaling scenario test

Drop autoscaling scenario test. It has always been skipped, so there
is no loss of test coverage. It takes a very long time to run since
it uses real alarms to perform 4 scaling operations.

See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122320/.

Change-Id: If37f63565a235c6128566f8f2cd993ed247f0912
Partially-implements: bp/tempest-client-scenarios

Migrate TestStampPattern to tempest client

Migrate TestStampPattern to tempest client. The test is currently
disabled in the gate, so this will be tested by adding a temp
patch on top removing the skip.

Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

subject: Allow policies to inspect dictionaries in the credentials using dot syntax

[{'account_id': 13341, 'date': '2014-09-24 23:06:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2014-09-24 23:07:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 13341, 'date': '2014-09-24 23:10:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 13341, 'date': '2014-09-25 00:02:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
loading configuration parameters from trove-manage better

It is a pain to load the configuration parameters when setting up
a new environment. Since theres no way to get the uuid of the
datastore version that is created you must get it by looking in
the database.

Closes-Bug: #1371297
Change-Id: If8cea0aaf38878bb04abe6e27b9bfd77d5684bce

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-07 20:05:21.000000000', 'message': 'In some cases, guest agents may leave temporary config files

The code in these three places manipulates the configuration files. I
was (admittedly) having more than the acceptable dose of failures in
execute_with_timeout() and one of them that failed was the move of the
my.cnf file. And this left a turd in /tmp.

Found that the same kind of thing can happen in cassandra and
mongo. Since default umask is 664, this leaves a file with somewhat
questionable permissions and potentially (at least for MySQL) some
passwords in /tmp

Change-Id: I93302fc5b1b18c9dd7116370a945b94d1824c75a
Closes-Bug: #1354136
'}, {'created': '2014-08-07 20:14:38.000000000', 'message': 'In some cases, guest agents may leave temporary config files

The code in these three places manipulates the configuration files. I
was (admittedly) having more than the acceptable dose of failures in
execute_with_timeout() and one of them that failed was the move of the
my.cnf file. And this left a turd in /tmp.

Found that the same kind of thing can happen in cassandra and
mongo. Since default umask is 664, this leaves a file with somewhat
questionable permissions and potentially (at least for MySQL) some
passwords in /tmp

commit_message:
In some cases, guest agents may leave temporary config files

The code in these three places manipulates the configuration files. I
was (admittedly) having more than the acceptable dose of failures in
execute_with_timeout() and one of them that failed was the move of the
my.cnf file. And this left a turd in /tmp. The failures I was having
with execute_with_timeout relate to other tests that were improperly
mocking/unmocking and some of those problems have now been fixed.

Found that the same kind of thing can happen in cassandra and
mongo. Since default umask is 664, this leaves a file with somewhat
questionable permissions and potentially (at least for MySQL) some
passwords in /tmp.

The files will now be deleted.

Some test cases have been added to exercise the code paths(s) in
mongo, cassandra and mysql. The tests verify that the files are
actually deleted by mocking the os.unlink call. setUp and tearDown
have been updated in each case to make sure that the monkey patching
is properly reversed.

Change-Id: I93302fc5b1b18c9dd7116370a945b94d1824c75a
Closes-Bug: #1354136

commit_message:
Use None instead of mutables in method params default values

Mutables in the method params defaults might cause errors and
that's why it's anti-pattern in most of the cases and should be
removed.

Change-Id: Ib1498e68ab9cc770b237a324b733c85b4a5c6839

[{'created': '2014-09-24 16:05:18.000000000', 'message': 'WIP Reduce the scope of RT work while holding the big lock

This makes the RT.update_available_resource() method do what it
can in the way of prep work before grabbing the lock to update

commit_message:
Reduce the scope of RT work while holding the big lock

This makes the RT.update_available_resource() method do what it
can in the way of prep work before grabbing the lock to update
the database stats.

Change-Id: I1132e2ab99427688529566c1a1fffb33eab07f3f
Related-Bug: #1371677

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V issue due to ML2 RPC versioning

The ML2 RPC version 1.1 breaks the hyper-v agent and
consequentially the RPC version in the Hyper-V agent needs
to be set to 1.1 to match the ML2 RPC base API version.

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/hyperv/agent/hyperv_neutron_agent.py

(cherry picked from commit 771327adbe9e563506f98ca561de9ded4d987698)

Change-Id: Idc4ae8d7dcff4331aca148a8f2a7a2b01679b3a8
Closes-Bug: #1353697

commit_message:
Add database charset during create

When using MySQL, the database charset should be utf-8.

And the default charset is latin1, which will causes glance db sync
failed.

Change-Id: Ic0a0ac33938836c7ec3035e677c837d0306c619e
Closes-bug: #1356887

I have to admit, 404 seems like the most appropriate response code for requesting a page that doesn't exist? Sure, it could be called a bad request - but 404 is just a more specific code for this particular bad request!

Im not going to -1 though, since if Pecan lands the change we have no choice but to accept this for our tests to continue working!"}, {'account_id': 8005, 'date': '2014-09-24 12:19:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

See, I disagree on the appropriateness of the 400 here.  For the scenario/test in question, the `get_all` method (https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/master/designate/api/v2/controllers/recordsets.py) has one required argument in the function signature (in zone_id), so it's actually a *TypeError* that's potentially being avoided here; the test is not providing that required function argument via the URL.  Pecan has had this code for awhile (which causes the 400 to be thrown), but because of your use of additional decorators, the signature inspection of the controller has failed (causing pecan to mistakenly fall back to a 404 instead - which you all have codified in your test)."}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-09-24 16:55:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> For the scenario/test in question, the `get_all` method (https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/master/designate/api/v2/controllers/recordsets.py) has one required argument in the function signature (in zone_id)

I think I'm looking at this from a different angle, as an end-user of the API with no knowledge of the code itself - I would expect all non-existing URLs to return a 404.. And, /zones/recordsets does not exist, so a 404 is IMO appropriate.

Maybe there's another way to ensure a 404 is returned when a controller is unable to match a route for the request?"}, {'account_id': 8005, 'date': '2014-09-24 19:27:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Okay, I'm thinking about dropping this in favor of another approach in pecan..."}, {'account_id': 8005, 'date': '2014-09-24 21:39:56.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Solving this a different way with changes to pecan.'}]

commit_message:
Correct a test that's broken in future versions of pecan

A bug in pecan causes HTTP 404 to be returned instead of a more correct 400.
Update this test for compatability with older and the latest version of pecan.

Change-Id: Ibd8fd9e0f1bfab5394cd754e0c4e794ec545bca7

Convergence will not cover all that HARestarter does.  Convergence does not create a webhook that can be hit to cause replacements.'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-09-16 19:55:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You can continue to use HARestarter while its deprecated, but we need to communicate somehow that this resource has issues which we don't plan to fix, and discourage users from creating new templates which use it."}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:20:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Users will need to see a plan for how they can connect a Ceilometer alarm to something that will delete and recreate a user-chosen set of resources, before they will be comfortable with a plan to retire HARestarter.  It will not make sense to retire HARestarter until such alternative functionality is available.  In the interim we can not tell users to avoid writing templates that use the only available way to get a desirable job done.'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-09-24 20:15:22.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

OS::Heat::HARestarter has issues which can't be easily fixed, so
we should discourage its use. The convergence features targeted
for Kilo will provide a more general solution.

Change-Id: I6f3ca644d0b726870b2d2361900fd4bc83c1c723
Closes-Bug: #1196479
"}]
commit_message:
Deprecate OS::Heat::HARestarter

OS::Heat::HARestarter has issues which can't be easily fixed, so
we should discourage its use. The convergence features targeted
for Kilo will provide a more general solution.

Change-Id: I6f3ca644d0b726870b2d2361900fd4bc83c1c723
Closes-Bug: #1196479

commit_message:
Fix 'createImage' server actions for V2.1 API

'createImage' server actions was missed for V2.1 API.
This patch converts 'createImage' server action for V2.1 API

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Change-Id: I5490365c72082b1652ddda2fed97c754fceeed22
Closes-Bug: #1367633

Use correct name for python-oslo-sphinx

import the namespaced version.

We're currently optimizing a tempest http image test by having it
use the local horizon login page as the external http source for a
test image. However, infrequent horizon failures in the gate are
now causing this to fail leading to false negatives.  This updates

commit_message:
Point TEMPEST_HTTP_IMAGE at git.openstack.org

We're currently optimizing a tempest http image test by having it
use the local horizon login page as the external http source for a
test image. However, infrequent horizon failures in the gate are
now causing this to fail leading to false negatives.  This updates
tempest.conf to instead use the cgit index at git.openstack.org.

Change-Id: I3595b0a65e91303977f13485aaac5d78b2c61ff7
Closes-bug: #1347692

commit_message:
$list.skip($start).take($count) throw YAQL exception

It was possible to have
 - $l: $list.skip($start)
 - Return: $l.take($count)

but not $list.skip($start).take($count)

Change-Id: I58709f9c994ad22497ff23662a1fc0c9c2d1e88d
Closes-Bug: #1365146

Instead of having a sync api exposing async results in a
synchronous manner we can provide a asynchronous api by
just using a simple executor and using the futures that it
returns to map into the tooz async result concept.

This moves the simplistic methods that are not using the
retry decorator to being actually async, in a future change

Change-Id: I39d86da24b3f559890df12095ebde837e2820c63
'}]
commit_message:
Use futures to make parts of the memcached driver async

Instead of having a sync api exposing async results in a
synchronous manner we can provide a asynchronous api by
just using a simple executor and using the futures that it
returns to map into the tooz async result concept.

This moves the simplistic methods that are not using the
retry decorator to being actually async, in a future change
the retry decorated ones can be altered as well...

Change-Id: I39d86da24b3f559890df12095ebde837e2820c63

commit_message:
Introduce designate:config to manage custom options

This designate::config is aim to use designate config resources
to manage custom configurations in designate config files.

This will make end user easy to add their own custom options
in Hiera data.

Fully implements blueprint designate-custom-config

Change-Id: I11a4cd53ae68113341e8b0851c68c9d09c362e86

commit_message:
Update designate::db::mysql backend

Use openstacklib::db::mysql to replace mysql module related classes.
b/c designate::db::mysql didn't use mysql_module option, so it's not
necessary to add warning info.

Change-Id: I250dde270b2563a537833f062028d5e68222b732

commit_message:
Remove commented configuration of the intersphinx module

The intersphinx module should not be used. Remove commented configuration
of the intersphinx module to not enable it in the future.

Change-Id: I165529af3d1a1ff720d9731592d7668f6f53abd2
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Define separate horizon.conf for tuskar-ui

We need special horizon.conf when tuskar-ui plugin is used,
so we can make static files from horizon available.

Change-Id: I72af7156ad3ff1b09cae4337f78e4ab7307f0a75

commit_message:
Add a required 'args' to do_list()

It seems all do_*() functions need an "args" parameter.
Although it's deprecated, it should still work.

Change-Id: Id4f392b275ca231bdea584a0d68ec177c5ebeaaa
Closes-bug: #1373219

commit_message:
Add unit test to cinder cgsnapshot api

This patch adds unit tests to cgsnapshot create api,
in case cgsnapshot is invalid or can not be found.

Change-Id: I6ec73b8db413e5c085f8a48830f5e1446c2d7240

commit_message:
Deprecate unused entries in cfg.py

backup_namespace and restore_namespace are now referenced on a
per-datastore basis. Having them in the common options is now no
longer useful. Deleted them from the common_options and marked them as
deprecated in the datastores.

Change-Id: I2d021d68c483b77f9426d78685a06fb0733ec5e9
Closes-Bug: #1351545

commit_message:
Add postgresql to notification_service_id option

The Trove 'notification_service_id' option has a default value for all
supported databases, except postgresql.

PostgreSQL now has a default value as well.

Change-Id: I033884bc36ba4ffe3faaf6cc4e3496cfb757858b
Closes-Bug: #1373083

[{'created': '2014-09-18 22:15:26.000000000', 'message': "Downgrade 'infinite' and 'unknown' capacity in weigher

When FilterScheduler was first introduced into Cinder, drivers were
required for the first time to report capacity. Some drivers preferred
to report 'infinite' or 'unknown' capacity because they were doing
thin-provisioning or the total capacity kept increasing. Now that we
have better support for thin-provisioning and we do find unrealistic
capacity couldn't do us any good in making optimal scheduling decision,
because 'infinite' and 'unknown' would always have the highest weight
when the weight multiplier is positive, which in most cases it is.

Drivers are expected to avoid sending 'infinite' 'unknown' capacity
anymore, instead, should report an actual real number for total/free
capacity.

This fix doesn't fix the driver, instead a small tweak is added to
CapacityWeigher in order to downgrade those drivers who report
'infinite' or 'unknown' as free capacity.  In particular, those who
report 'infinite'/'unknown' free capacity will be adjusted to be the
one has lowest weight, no matter in 'spreading' (weight multiplier>0)
or 'stacking' (weight multiplier<0) mode.

Change-Id: Ied087386a1a2f43e6a77499a817d5c637ef448f6
Partial-fix: #1350638

commit_message:
Downgrade 'infinite' and 'unknown' capacity in weigher

When FilterScheduler was first introduced into Cinder, drivers were
required for the first time to report capacity. Some drivers preferred
to report 'infinite' or 'unknown' capacity because they were doing
thin-provisioning or the total capacity kept increasing. Now that we
have better support for thin-provisioning and we do find unrealistic
capacity couldn't do us any good in making optimal scheduling decision,
because 'infinite' and 'unknown' would always have the highest weight
when the weight multiplier is positive, which in most cases it is.

Drivers are expected to avoid sending 'infinite' 'unknown' capacity
anymore, instead, should report an actual real number for total/free
capacity.

This fix doesn't fix the driver, instead a small tweak is added to
CapacityWeigher in order to downgrade those drivers who report
'infinite' or 'unknown' as free capacity.  In particular, those who
report 'infinite'/'unknown' free capacity will be adjusted to be the
one has lowest weight, no matter in 'spreading' (weight multiplier>0)
or 'stacking' (weight multiplier<0) mode.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ied087386a1a2f43e6a77499a817d5c637ef448f6
Partial-bug: #1350638

commit_message:
Add specific docs build option to tox

Add doc venv to align with other OpenStack projects (such as keystone,
heat and nova) who are using 'docs' for their doc builds.

Change-Id: I8bccbf9c6b1eae5de9f74396fd5159662ad04149

commit_message:
Sync network_info if instance not found before _build_resources yield

If instance is deleted before _build_resources yield, there won't
waiting for network_info sync finish.

So there is race case, when the exception catching for
'InstanceNotFound' in do_build_and_run_instance invoke
'_cleanup_allocated_networks', the '_allocate_network_async' didn't
create port yet. After '_cleanup_allocated_networks' finished,
'_allocate_network_async' create new port for the instance, but there
isn't any cleanup for the new port anymore.

Change-Id: I5027a1aaeb9a2106f7982fd0422f88c4caa20ffb
Related-Bug: #1357055

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Update settings.py to resolve UncompressableFileError

The latest Horizon master requires xstatic.pkg.bootstrap_datepicker
library and an updated settings.py that imports it correctly,
otherwise there will be a fatal UncompressableFileError.
We need to reflect the latest horizon settings.py in dashboard

Change-Id: I3cd4b2a62b9df534ca55df4f4554b53d94f304cb
Closes-Bug: 1373048
