(2 comments)

I wish I've seen that original bug 1271331 when it happen. The fix for it was very wrong. The issue is that subprocess manages to call original os.read instead of greened one. This cannot be fixed by repeating communicate() because then we lose the part of output that has been caught already.

I think the problem is with monkey-patching happening late in (Trove?) tests.

As per Python issue, it is totally a problem with either eventlet or Trove tests (and Nova ones too AFAIU)."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-08-05 12:17:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Yes, I agree that the fix for 1271331 was bad and just retrying communicate couldn't have ever worked (it'd have hit this problem).

I agree with you on the loss of stdout on the retry; communicate() isn't setup to handle that.

So another option here is to just handle the error with a retry but that's not always safe (not all commands can just be re-run).

The only PROPER solution to this in the OpenStack code is to throw a ProcessExecutionError back to the caller and get the fix into Python.

----

To your comment about the problem being with monkey-patching in Python, I don't think that is the case. Here's why I believe that.

(a) Assume that we didn't monkeypatch green/eventlet at all.

(b) Assume that we did a subprocess.Popen() and provided stdin, stdout and stderr descriptors (NOT subprocess.PIPE) and those fd's already had been set to non-blocking.

communicate() is partially setup to handle it.

The incomplete part is the age-old issue with non-blocking fd's in that even when select() tells you that the call to (read/write) won't block, you could get EWOULDBLOCK (aka EAGAIN).

And _communicate() isn't setup to handle that.

Full disclosure: I may be wrong about this and not understand the aspect of monkey patching that you refer to. 

----

How do you propose we fix this for OpenStack? I see the following options (and their attended consequences).

(a) use the hack I've proposed (yes, it is a hack, I know it). The risk is that you may get partial stdout and stderr. 

(b) attempt to retry. i.e. do another Popen and communicate() again. The risk is that not all commands are just re-runnable. Maybe we only do this if the caller sets attempts > 1? Then it is up to the caller to determine whether the operation is restartable or not.

(c) Toss a ProcessExecutionError back to caller. This will result in a high incidence of test failures and potentially failures in production as well."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-08-05 12:40:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I propose option D - ensure that monkey-patching happens properly wherever this issue shows up, fix all projects.

We can add a warning "Got EAGAIN. It seems you've set up your eventlet wrong. Fix your code!"

It seems the issue happens in trove because there is some monkey_patch missing or probably because subprocess doesn't get monkey-patched by default.

This is not Python issue - communicate() method is not supposed to work after failure. It might be an eventlet issue (somehow subprocess got patched w/o os).'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-08-05 13:02:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yuriy, there is a python issue in that communicate() should handle a non-blocking socket properly.

It isn't that communicate() should handle a second call; that is a bug in OpenStack code.

What monkey-patch do you contend is missing?"}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-08-06 18:26:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-08-07 00:26:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-07 00:26:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-31 12:17:59.000000000', 'message': 'Handle the possibility of a failure in communicate()

This is a workaround for Python issue 22114 which is a problem with
retrying a communicate() call if stdin was provided in the earlier
call to Popen. For a full description of the problem, refer to bug
1347337 (the bug this fixes) and the python issue which is at
http://bugs.python.org/issue22114

Change-Id: I2450d2dc425a3d29eaba4d5ff9badc4a992a0ec8
Closes-Bug: #1347337
'}, {'created': '2014-07-31 12:28:56.000000000', 'message': 'Handle the possibility of a failure in communicate()

This is a workaround for Python issue 22114 which is a problem with
retrying a communicate() call if stdin was provided in the earlier
call to Popen. For a full description of the problem, refer to bug
1347337 (the bug this fixes) and the python issue which is at
http://bugs.python.org/issue22114

Change-Id: I2450d2dc425a3d29eaba4d5ff9badc4a992a0ec8
Closes-Bug: #1347337
'}, {'created': '2014-08-07 00:26:44.000000000', 'message': "Handle a failure on communicate()

After much debugging of the subject bug, we've concluded that a
failure and an exception of OSError with EAGAIN from communicate()
indicates some monkey business. In the specific case that we're seeing
in Trove, it is because monkey patching didn't quite get done the way
it should.

In any event, retrying isn't the answer.  This change reverts an
earlier change that retried the communicate() call and instead hurls
the OSError exception back to the caller. A test case to fake the
communicate() failure has been amended to ensure that we handle this
in what we believe now to be the right way.

Change-Id: I2450d2dc425a3d29eaba4d5ff9badc4a992a0ec8
Closes-Bug: #1347337
"}, {'created': '2014-08-07 10:58:00.000000000', 'message': "Handle a failure on communicate()

commit_message:
Handle a failure on communicate()

After much debugging of the subject bug, we've concluded that a
failure and an exception of OSError with EAGAIN from communicate()
indicates some monkey business. In the specific case that we're seeing
in Trove, it is because monkey patching didn't quite get done the way
it should.

In any event, retrying isn't the answer.  This change reverts an
earlier change that retried the communicate() call and instead hurls
the OSError exception back to the caller, if we are out of retries. A
test case to fake the communicate() failure has been amended to ensure
that we handle this in what we believe now to be the right way.

This change was merged in oslo.concurrency as Change-Id
Ie36d77eebb2c20124a61ff6029c3b97bfffb9427

Change-Id: I2450d2dc425a3d29eaba4d5ff9badc4a992a0ec8
Closes-Bug: #1347337
Related-Bug: #1365736

commit_message:
Remove 'detail' dimension, fix a couple bugs

The 'detail' dimension in http_check is not actually an appropriate
dimension since it does not contain data which _identifies_ a metric.
This data is valuable, though, and will be captured and made available
in a future enhancement.

Bug fixes:
- Fix unix.py crash on EFI mountpoints which return 0 available inodes
- Rename 'service_name' to 'name' in nagios_wrapper for ServicesCheck
  compatibility
- Update nagios_wrapper YAML example for naming convention

Change-Id: I44877a856fac84f54ca764a79e75ace9f90d9302

commit_message:
Add _wrap_db_error support for postgresql

The original "_wrap_db_error" function is only available for mysql.
We need to add support for postgresql.

The deadlock exception thrown from postgresql is TransactionRollbackError,
it's not the same with "OperationalError" thrown from mysql,
and isn't included in sqlalchemy. So, the base exception need to be
catched.

Change-Id: I439a4e0c431c9446ffabd1c93f11b8f509b1ebd7
Closes-Bug: #1270725
(cherry picked from commit 3a6a5b01a72e0e20787f3d6a47f6f0c0262dbbeb)

Fix test_migration_common with python3.3

Replace usage of contextlib.nested() with actual nested 'with' statements.

Change-Id: I8d2488695a8626117dff29b0c080dd4f027af4c4

Yu Zhang: Please see the bug comment from Christopher Yeoh at https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1320754.  Basically, the flavor-id that is referenced by the instance is not unique.  So a flavor being used can "disappear", but another can be created with the same flavor-id, but different specs.  We really have no way to guarantee that the flavor is truly the one that was originally picked, since flavor-id is not unique.

The existing check in nova/api/openstack/compute/servers.py would guarantee that the flavor exists before creating the instance.  This happens before _provision_instances in nova/nova/compute/api.py.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-21 04:26:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

commit_message:
Prevent in-use flavors from being deleted

A flavor can be created or deleted at any time, no matter if
an instance references it or not. Since instances reference
the flavor by their 'flavor-id', which is not unique, you
can create, delete, and re-create the flavor using the same
flavor-id. This could cause issues with instance actions, e.g.
resize or rescue, because a re-created flavor with the same
flavor-id could have a different configuration. This patch
prevents a flavor from being deleted if it is in-use by an
instance.

Change-Id: I862d267bca41934f9150ffa4441ce0a24a61bc38
Closes-Bug: #1320754

commit_message:
Add retry_on_deadlock decorator

Decorating an sqlalchemy db api method with retry_on_deadlock will
result in an automatic retry when a DBDeadlock exception is encountered.

Cinder, Glance, and Nova all have a copy of this decorator.  Now it is
needed by Heat.

Change-Id: If76b80fefa3a3fd7efce2433069af07efdb9fdfd

[{'created': '2014-09-18 08:19:15.000000000', 'message': "Removes bogus negative create image compute

Removes test_create_image_specify_multibyte_character_image_name
as it is not a valid test. It currently does not send an
invalid utf-8 sequence, but a valid unicode one. Also we can't actually
send an invalid utf-8 sequence via JSON as it is not possible to
encode an invalid UTF-8 sequence into a series of unicode characters
which is what JSON uses as strings. So its not possible for it
to fail this way. And we don't do XML testing for this type of test.

Change-Id: I39b5c017c8a173f8dd56a14c1bc7dc6952ac787d
Partially-Closes: 1006725
"}]
commit_message:
Removes bogus negative create image compute

Removes test_create_image_specify_multibyte_character_image_name
as it is not a valid test. It currently does not send an
invalid utf-8 sequence, but a valid unicode one. Also we can't actually
send an invalid utf-8 sequence via JSON as it is not possible to
encode an invalid UTF-8 sequence into a series of unicode characters
which is what JSON uses as strings. So its not possible for it
to fail this way. And we don't do XML testing for this type of test.

Change-Id: I39b5c017c8a173f8dd56a14c1bc7dc6952ac787d
Partially-Closes: 1006725

'}]
commit_message:
fix memory leak for _safe_log

In _safe_log it use recursive closure. The gc can not free stack for
those recursive closure for cycle-reference. So cut down the cycle
to fix it.

Resolved Bug #1365892

commit_message:
Delete the token and endpoint on expiry of token of client

This change will guarantee that clients using this module will
renew the session on token expiry. Currently this fact causes
the issues with Ceilometer client and its usage in the
ceilometer-alarm-evaluator.

Co-Authored-By: vaibhav_kale <vaibhav_kale@persistent.co.in> 
Related-Bug: #1357343
Change-Id: I10b8c4c9d6aa4ce74028e91cc5e8a85e47e6953b

commit_message:
Fixup Fixtures Use in db test classes.

With Fixture objects and test cases it is important to upcall first
rather than later to allow base classes to configure their internal
test tracking state. Failing to do so allows bugs like this one to
occur - when failure occurs early, the state required to gather
environmental details about the failure is not prepared, and the
test machinery will raise secondary exceptions as it tries to do that.

This may even obscure the original error.

I've taken a fairly minimal approach here - I think it would be
possible and likely even desirable to get rid of the test classes
altogether - this module appears to have very little, if any, actual
test code - its all glue for managing the test database connections.
However I know zzzeek is working on a fairly large reorg in this
area and I don't want to conceptually clash with that - we can do
further cleanups later.

Change-Id: Ic9f24aa2352d097a10be8420b701fa9f588b21b0
Closes-Bug: #1330763

commit_message:
Remove config parameter from secret_store.py interface

When the barbican.plugins.secret_store.py interface was added, the
existing HSM-style plugins were placed into an adapter module called
store_crypto.py. Since this module, unlike other secret-store
technologies such as Dogtag or KMIP requires access to lower level data
store resources such as KEKDatum, these resources were added to a
'context' parameter. Unfortunately all secret_store.py implementors had
to inherit this contract. Hence this CR removes that constraint, and
starts the process of moving towards singleton-based repository
instances.

Note as well that the secret_store.py module now has 100% unit test
coverage.

Change-Id: I7094beb4d593a6ac7a9de3cb818ac455f5c6ec1b

[{'created': '2014-07-25 01:39:12.000000000', 'message': 'Log stdout, stderr and command on execute() error

It would help debugging considerably if a failure in execute()
generated a message (at a client specified logging level). This is bug
1342857. Such a message, generated by execute() would only occur if
the user requested it by specifying a parameter (verbose), and

would include properly sanitized information. As an example, this

It would help debugging considerably if a failure in execute()

message, generated by execute() would only occur if the user requested
it by specifying a parameter (log_errors), and execute() were to throw
an exception. As an example, this change would address the issue being

commit_message:
Log stdout, stderr and command on execute() error

It would help debugging considerably if a failure in execute()
generated a message (at a client specified logging level). Such a
message, generated by execute() would only occur if the user requested
it by specifying a parameter (log_errors), and execute() were to throw
an exception. As an example, this change would address the issue being
addressed in bug 1340124 for the Trove project only.

DocImpact: New parameter added to processutils.execute().  The
possible values of the log_errors parameter are 'all' or 'final'. The
default value of None implies no logging. If it is set to 'final',
stdout and stderr are logged on the final failure. If it is set to
'all', stdout and stderr are logged on every failure.

DocImpact:
Change-Id: If8180e042e1a05374ef705f5873cc0981243619f
Closes-Bug: #1342857
Suggested-By: Peter Stachowski <peter@tesora.com>
Reported-By: Ionuț Arțăriși <iartarisi@suse.cz>

rpc, notifier: remove deprecated modules

Let's remove that altogether now that everybody migrated to oslo.messaging.

commit_message:
Cleanup and adding timing to lockutils logging

* Cleanup lockutils logging by showing lock name and function in same
line.  The enables easier parsing of information related to lock
acquisition from logs.

* Logs time a thread spent waiting on locks, as well as time spent
holding locks.  This will make it easier to debug suboptimal locking.

Change-Id: I1bc8d27eb03b43f79954a425d6bdc92ede85b0d0

commit_message:
Making action controller able to handler multiple actions

* Added action service similar to workflow service
* Added ActionListSpec to represent a top level action list
* Changed action controller to call action service properly
* Added required unit tests
* Other minor changes

Change-Id: Iebbefab6168cdc167e5c2d9ad7fe806d431f0cef

commit_message:
Update stdlib dependency to 4.x

ironic's dependency on stdlib 2.3.0 is out of sync with the other
openstack modules. This is a problem because it is not possible to
install this module alongside the other openstack modules because of the
dependency conflicts. This patch fixes the issue by updating the
depenency on stdlib to 4.x. The stdlib functions currently in use in
ironic have carried on through 4.x.

Change-Id: I8d8f11049587b0d1e5a66914224d7ed922e51c4d

commit_message:
Update stdlib dependency to 4.x

puppetlabs/stdlib 4.x is backwards compatible with 3.x and still tested
on Puppet 2.7. Updating stdlib to 4.x allows modules to use newer
functions without breaking older functionality.

Change-Id: Id7707932c96f2cbd997f136b9257825ca8dee7f8

commit_message:
Update stdlib dependency to 4.x

puppetlabs/stdlib 4.x is backwards compatible with 3.x and still tested
on Puppet 2.7. Updating stdlib to 4.x allows modules to use newer
functions without breaking older functionality.

Change-Id: Iaaac5678cdd00db3a03eb1f715e6cd91a25cefc8

The drivers should only be raising IronicExceptions for power-related
methods, so this patch changes ironic.conductor.utils.node_power_action()
to can catch (and reraise) IronicExceptions instead of any Exception.

Drivers that handled exceptions from node_power_action() are also
changed to handle IronicExceptions instead of Exceptions.

commit_message:
Raise IronicExceptions in node_power_action()

ironic.conductor.utils.node_power_action() catches any Exceptions but
raises IronicExceptions instead.

Drivers that handled exceptions from node_power_action() now
catch IronicExceptions instead of Exceptions.

Change-Id: I592f09b953355cf02083a0303a3204de247e4b46
Partial-Bug: #1267693

commit_message:
Add missing methods for firewall driver

Commit If19be8579ca734a899cdd673c919eee8165aaa0e introduced an enhanced
rpc to update securitygroup info in securitygroups_rpc.py. But class
SecurityGroupAgentRpcCallbackMixin is inherited by all neutron agents
which some adopt their own firewall driver which does not have below
methods defined such as HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver. When those agents
start, it will raise AttributeError for these methods. So add them into
top firewall driver class.

update_security_group_rules
update_security_group_members

Closes-Bug: #1370342
Change-Id: I464cd141abea92b7d474ed428389540ac3d29ff9

commit_message:
Update stdlib dependency to 4.x

puppetlabs/stdlib 4.x is backwards compatible with 3.x and still tested
on Puppet 2.7. Updating stdlib to 4.x allows modules to use newer
functions without breaking older functionality.

Change-Id: Ia100f0bde5a27fb4a28d3918742460163305dd8c

commit_message:
Fix metadata constriant for Common

A patch went in that needed attributes in Common and the image
metadata was change to ~> 10.0.1 which worked until Common
was recently bumped to 10.1.  The metadata for Common should have had
a minor version bump, not a patch bump for the new attributes.

Change-Id: Ie46a83ec7b59cb1895978296628e857302c290a8
Closes-Bug: #1373008

commit_message:
Enable the neutron dhcp and l3 agents

These need to be enabled in order for the upstart service to be allowed
to start, they are controlled by os-svc-enable-upstart as
OS_SVC_ENABLE_CONTROL is set in their upstart configs.

Change-Id: I20e2e4a672fcd124ba3e64ec9728d184c6ed0c22

commit_message:
Plugin/DB additions for version 2 of LBaaS API

Added alembic migrations, models, db methods and plugin methods.
Added DEFERRED status for entities not linked to a load balancer.
Added to_dict method in BaseNeutron model.
Sql Alchemy models in its own module.
Plugin database methods are accessed by composition through the plugin.
Added data models to convert sql alchemy models before passing to driver.

Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement

Change-Id: Iaec2c2315ae54418b341eb31e6b3ff53b02ca9d7
Co-authored-by: Brandon Logan <brandon.logan@rackspace.com>
Co-authored-by: Vijayendra Bhamidipati <vbhamidipati@paypal.com>
Co-authored-by: Craig Tracey <Craig.Tracey@gmail.com>

is_block_dev attribute was mistakenly set to True for RBD images
(we don't actually map RBD images to block devices in the *host*
system, but only in *guests*, so as far as the host system is
concerned an RBD image must not be treated like a system block
device). This led to a situation when mkfs was called for a non

commit_message:
Fix instance boot when Ceph is used for ephemeral storage

is_block_dev attribute was mistakenly set to True for RBD images
(we don't actually map RBD images to block devices in the *host*
system, but only in *guests*, so as far as the host system is
concerned an RBD image must not be treated like a system block
device). This led to a situation when mkfs was called for a non
existing file and failed when trying to create an ephemeral fs.

Closes-Bug: #1362221

Change-Id: I54c0d117a53bb61f278b2e137bd29a595548f5a1
(cherry picked from commit e9eb1d69bf75c22b0ad4b50e4892a5644c78cf68)

commit_message:
Limit number of API workers used

Environments with large numbers of CPUs will create a large
number of workers which can have an unnecessarily large
impact on memory usage, particular where you know how many
workers are needed.

Related devstack change: Ie4bb075310a61a0873c9e56e4974600dbb4794a1

Change-Id: I0dc18d069a6a9c27ec1ae711c8746c6444d514da

commit_message:
Remove XenAPI driver

The XenAPI driver does not have known users and does not meet
the minimum requirements for Cinder drivers.

This patch removes the driver from the tree.

Closes-bug: 1372836

Change-Id: I2123b2d52180bbdffe90c458f115c67f50dfd5e9

commit_message:
Do not use the context parameter on refresh()

Now all RPC objects already have a context embedded within them so we
can ignore the context parameter on the refresh() method (it was the
last method using this parameter). This patch also:

* Update the Docstrings from the @remotable methods to let the user know
  that the context parameter is not being used. The @remotable decorator
  still requires that the method it's decorating have a context as it's
  first argument, but that's going to change in the future.

* All code and tests were updated to not pass the context to refresh(),
  save() and destroy() methods.

Closes-Bug: #1314732
Change-Id: Ibb338b909d99862ae048d605e66b8831d8c2128d

commit_message:
Always split template names on forward slash

Template names in Django always use forward slash, even on Windows,
so to parse them properly, split on forward slash instead of
os.path.sep which is '\\' on Windows.

Change-Id: Ib72b379397f014aa1e4557fed02cbac5d931b84e
Closes-Bug: #1371610
Co-Authored-By: Timur Sufiev <tsufiev@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix scenarios not passing down specific network

Nova v2 api expects nics in specific networks to be passed
down in an array of "networks". nics is used in novaclient
but converted to networks in
python-novaclient/tree/novaclient/v1_1/servers.py#n520

Apply the conversion to the parameters to make the check
pass in case where there would be multiple networks
matching the requirements. Also remove a case where scenario
manager forced in the wrong network into the tests.

Closes-Bug: #1368834
Change-Id: Ic0b87377c5878e240a0fbcc6549023c828dd97ab

problem. First, the rest of Congress uses eventlets instead
of threads. The DSE should follow what the rest of Congress
uses and also use eventlets. The fix for that problem is to
make the DSE use eventlets rather than threads. The second
problem is that threads are not very scalable in Python and
there is a lack of performance because of Python's GIL, which
only allows one thread to execute at a time. That is not
useful in the situation of the DSE since we want multiple
lines of code to execute at a time because multiple services
are running at once. The fix for that problem is also to
switch the DSE to using eventlets rather than threads.

change the DSE to use eventlets rather than threads. Instead of
the d6service class inheriting from threading.Thread, it now
inherits from eventlet.greenlet.greenlet, which makes d6service
now an eventlet rather than a thread. This will fix scalability
issues as I mentioned above, and also make the DSE use eventlets
like the rest of Congress does.

Change-Id: Ib9c62e3942f1127bb58b398a98f2844bf7669869

commit_message:
Changed DSE to use eventlets rather than threads

Implements: blueprint dse

The current problem is that the DSE uses threads rather than
eventlets. This problem has two main issues that make it a
problem. First, the rest of Congress uses eventlets instead
of threads. The DSE should follow what the rest of Congress
uses and also use eventlets. The fix for that problem is to
make the DSE use eventlets rather than threads. The second
problem is that threads are not very scalable in Python and
there is a lack of performance because of Python's GIL, which
only allows one thread to execute at a time. That is not
useful in the situation of the DSE since we want multiple
lines of code to execute at a time because multiple services
are running at once. The fix for that problem is also to
switch the DSE to using eventlets rather than threads.

The fix for these two problems, which this change does, is to
change the DSE to use eventlets rather than threads. Instead of
the d6service class inheriting from threading.Thread, it now
inherits from eventlet.greenthread.GreenThread, which makes d6service
now an eventlet rather than a thread. This will fix scalability
issues as I mentioned above, and also make the DSE use eventlets
like the rest of Congress does.

Changed the implementation so that the spawning of the green
threads is hidden from the user and they can initialize a
service by just using: Service() instead of having to use
deepsix.SpawnService(Service).

Change-Id: Ib9c62e3942f1127bb58b398a98f2844bf7669869

commit_message:
VMware: Store vCenter passwords in keystone credential store

This blueprint proposes an alternative way of storing vCenter user names and
passwords for OpenStack administrators that are leery of keeping them within
nova.conf as plain text.

blueprint vmware-encrypt-vcenter-passwords

Change-Id: If8b56491e3eae13b619bb795e3f7ce2f3864f96e

[{'created': '2014-09-23 15:20:15.000000000', 'message': "Miscellaneous last minute 5.1 fixes

operations/2410-galera-autorebuild -- couple syntax fixes

operations/2800-experimental -- added info about when you can
enable experimental features.  I kept it just a little vague,
given the state of Zabbix.

planning-guide/0010-intro -- made a bullet list of alternate ways
to run MOSt and added the same note as is in the Release Notes.

planning-guide/4000-planning-summary -- added vCenter, vSphere,
NSX, and Sahara to the list

planning-guide/4450-monitoring -- moved Ceilometer before Zabbix,
marked Zabbix as experimental.

preface/preface -- deleted 5.0 and 5.0.1 lines

Release Notes/010 -- experimental features can be enabled on a
running Fuel Master, not before it is installed.

commit_message:
Miscellaneous last minute 5.1 fixes

operations/2410-galera-autorebuild -- couple syntax fixes

operations/2800-experimental -- added info about when you can
enable experimental features.  I kept it just a little vague,
given the state of Zabbix.

planning-guide/0010-intro -- made a bullet list of alternate ways
to run MOSt and added the same note as is in the Release Notes.

planning-guide/4000-planning-summary -- added vCenter, vSphere,
NSX, and Sahara to the list

planning-guide/4450-monitoring -- moved Ceilometer before Zabbix,
marked Zabbix as experimental.

preface/preface -- deleted 5.0 and 5.0.1 lines

Release Notes/010 -- experimental features can be enabled on a
running Fuel Master, not before it is installed.

Release Notes/050-known-issues -- added LP1372825, that Zabbix
does not work.

Release Notes/060-obtain-the-product -- added Ron's new verbage
about Mirantis OpenStack Express

terminology/galera -- added two xrefs per Sergii Golovatiuk
terminology/experiemental-features -- a bit of rewording

User Guide -- config-environment/1000-assign-roles -- added note
that the Zabbix role is displayed only if experimental features
have been enabled.

Change-Id: I62c40bbe9dbc2bf6a5cf53bff605908ff18c2427

commit_message:
Miscellaneous last minute 5.1 fixes

operations/2410-galera-autorebuild -- couple syntax fixes

operations/2800-experimental -- added info about when you can
enable experimental features.  I kept it just a little vague,
given the state of Zabbix.

planning-guide/0010-intro -- made a bullet list of alternate ways
to run MOSt and added the same note as is in the Release Notes.

planning-guide/4000-planning-summary -- added vCenter, vSphere,
NSX, and Sahara to the list

planning-guide/4450-monitoring -- moved Ceilometer before Zabbix,
marked Zabbix as experimental.

preface/preface -- deleted 5.0 and 5.0.1 lines

Release Notes/010 -- experimental features can be enabled on a
running Fuel Master, not before it is installed.

Release Notes/050-known-issues -- added LP1372825, that Zabbix
does not work.

Release Notes/060-obtain-the-product -- added Ron's new verbage
about Mirantis OpenStack Express

terminology/galera -- added two xrefs per Sergii Golovatiuk
terminology/experiemental-features -- a bit of rewording

User Guide -- config-environment/1000-assign-roles -- added note
that the Zabbix role is displayed only if experimental features
have been enabled.

Change-Id: I62c40bbe9dbc2bf6a5cf53bff605908ff18c2427

commit_message:
Floating ip does not have an id

1) Floating ip does not have an id, it uses floating_ip_address
   as the key.
2) There is no attribute that is similar to a name.
3) Set resource_name for person friendly print.

Change-Id: I9e0d21dcf446ad19fe416a868e3ddfa804b99f36

commit_message:
Adding SSL/TLS protocol version checks

Bandit can now check for insecure SSL/TLS versions, bad versions
are defined in the config file. By default:
 - SSLv2 is bad
 - SSLv23 is bad
 - SSLv3 is bad
 - TLSv1 is bad

This check works with ssl and pyOpenSSL modules.
A second check will also catch default use of ssl.wrap_socket as
this will use SSLv23 if no option is given. This is an INFO level
check.

Change-Id: I5ff8ea7038eed41b09e4d0ebfcb59bfd7fd4c894

commit_message:
Upgrade/update instructions for 5.1; relnotes descriptions

This commit covers all the docs about upgrade and update
as well as refinements to the what-is, new-features, and
other-enhancements sections.

Includes change to use lrzuntar to unpack the 5.1 tarball
with a warning that the Fuel Master node requires 2GB RAM for
this to work, with a link to the hardware requirements for
the master

Includes corrections to the Release Notes Upgrade and Update sections
and to this information in the User Guide.

user-guide/cli.rst -- info from https://review.openstack.org/120428
about the update option.

Ref-Arch now includes 8000-fuel-upgrade that describes how
upgrade works

Release Notes are restructured to include:
- "Known Issues fixed in 5.1 and 5.0.2" is added in 117672
- "HA issues fixed in 5.1" is added in 117338

Change-Id: Ie2054b31ce216942fd64b5bf274d8efa7d300bc4
Closes-Bug: 1360372
Closes-Bug: 1367199

commit_message:
augment "Neutron with NSX topology" section

- we recommend to dispose NSX nodes in OpenStack Management network if
  possible
- rename Neutron_nsx_topology.png to _images/Neutron_nsx_l2.png that
  illustrates aformentioned topology
- otherwise NSX network must have L3 connectivity with OpenStack Public
  network; in this case Compute nodes must receive Public addresses
  (checkbox on Settings tab must be ticked)
- mention this in Known Issues for 5.1 release
- add figure for topology with L3 connectivity
- while here fix typo on figures ("Constrollers")

Change-Id: I6f7948a9bfa2b5c6e7cf6e8a3636d94f913a71d1
Closes-bug: #1367859

commit_message:
Information about VMware vCenter and NSX features is updated.

Following documents are updated:
- Terminology: links in the 'nsx' term added
- Planning guide:
-- Choose Network Topology: information about nsx added
-- Nodes and Roles: notes added
-- Preparing vSphere Integration: notes and limitations added
- Reference Architecture: notes added, HA setup diagram updated
- User Guide: screenshots updated, vcenter-deploy.rst updated,
  7310-nsx-deploy.rst, add screenshot with filled NSX settings

I added a link to the vCenter page for assigning roles.  The
screen shot was too small to really see the verbage about not
assigning a Controller node so I increased the size of that image
and others in the vicinity.

Implements: blueprint vcenter-documentation-update-fuel-5.1
Change-Id: Ibcb5c1b7cd2a286e2239d17d87ea49eb10930964

commit_message:
state the fact that NSX Service node is mandatory for Mirantis OpenStack

- NSX cluster can successfully operate without Service node, but our
  tests show that creation of virtual interfaces fails, due to incorrect
  configuration of `replication_mode' setting in Neutron NSX plugin
  confguration file (plugin is configured to use Service node)
- we need more work to be done to implement working Mirantis OpenStack
  with NSX cluster that operates without Service node
- note that OpenStack itself can be used with NSX cluster that lacks
  Service node
- while here add missing article

Change-Id: Ibd88834a525104f4c9e71c355c3e7e0ea833adba
Closes-bug: #1365043

commit_message:

Maybe we could even find a nice way to make the middleware itself flexible for a lot of different constraints."}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2014-08-14 19:52:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks for everyone that has looked at this patch so far. I'm going to try to comment on some of the points that were raised both here as well as on the IRC channel.


The initial idea was to create a mechanism where other storage policies (e.g., swiftonfile) could add a middleware to the proxy pipeline. This middleware would provide a callback method for the proxy server to call at the right time. The mem_constraints.py was created to serve as an example of such a middleware. The really big change is in the object controller where it checks if the 'swift.constraints' env. is set and calls that provided method instead of the default one.


The reason for not just describing the limits on swift.conf for each policy is that a third-party policy could have a different set of constraints and not just different limitations on the existins constraints. The best example I have at the moment is where swiftonfile doesn't just check the object length, but checks the length of each part of the object name that maps to a posix directory structure (e.g., 
"container/dir1/subdir2/obj"). The good thing about having the middleware for each storage policy is the flexibility it provides. For example, we could in the future have a set of constraints for the container name also based on storage policies.


I also had thought about creating a generic middleware, where it would load different policies callback methods (very similar to the current data migration patch), but that would require admins listing names of classes and methods in the configuration files and I was trying to avoid that, but I'm not totally against it.


Another option, is to pull the whole obj validation to the middleware and have it all happen there in one place. This is very nice because the validation would happen very early in the pipeline and could respond quickly on errors. It would require some refactoring around setting the content-length and would probably also mean providing paths to each policy callback function in a configuration file.


So I think there are multiple ways of doing this, we just need to find the best one. Please keep the feedback coming :)'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-08-14 21:12:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thiago, I think that's a good point, and something that we should absolutely support if there are per-policy constraints. Another example could be to have a _minimum_ object size for an EC policy.

If there are new checks for a storage policy, they can be done in the proxy (in which case a callback can be set up) or in the object (in which case you can make DiskFile-specific checks).

So i'm not sure the right way to proceed yet. Maybe this is actually two things."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-08-14 22:09:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I agree that there's two distinct things going on here.

First, the things we have in swift.conf now are artificial upper bounds placed on certain lengths in the system... max object length, max length of an individual metadatum, max total metadata length, et cetera.

An important property here is that the storage nodes don't really care. Swift can store as much object metadata as xfs will let us stuff into xattrs, and as much container metadata as you have disk space for. Want 2T objects? Works great (until a disk fills up). It's all enforced just at the proxy level.

This means that the limits can be varied over time, both by increasing and decreasing, and existing objects(/containers/accounts) don't suddenly become invalid. If a client PUTs a 5 GiB object and then I lower my max object size to 2 GiB, the client can still GET their 5 GiB object. Replication can still move it around the cluster as rebalancing happens.

Second, we have things like name restrictions: no null bytes, valid UTF-8, etc. These are things that the storage nodes *do* care about. If you get an object whose name is invalid UTF-8, that object might break the replicator when it tries to go through, or it might break the deserialization of xattrs or something (maybe not a bad name, but something might). This is the sort of restriction that you can't tighten on a given cluster, only loosen.

For example, if we added the restriction "UTF-8 object names" so that our code could assume UTF-8 everywhere, but there was an existing object /v1/a/c/foo\x00bar, that would break any code that assumed UTF-8. That object might fail to get replicated, GET requests might fail, container updates... all that stuff could go wrong.

The reason I bring it up here is that, if one diskfile has tighter restrictions than another, then adding such disks to an existing policy is akin to tightening the restrictions. If Swift-On-File chokes on multiple adjacent slashes, then one can't add a Swift-On-File-backed disk to any cluster (/storage policy) with existing objects in it lest those objects choke Swift-On-File.

Part of what I'm getting at is that per-storage-policy restrictions seem to be the wrong way to look at it. What we really want is additional global restrictions so that the cluster limits things to the *intersection* of the space of valid objects for all diskfiles that the cluster is ever going to consider using; that's the way to make sure existing data doesn't choke the cluster.

What I'd like to see is the artificial restrictions (category 1) being per-storage-policy, and that in core Swift. The other ones should probably be one diskfile's stuff per middleware, then operators can stack the middlewares and only objects that make it through the gauntlet can get uploaded.

I hope that makes sense; it's certainly a lot of words.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2014-08-18 04:27:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I imagine that a backend can report a request error in some way. If some errors are not reportable, then perhaps we can fix up controller's .best_response() so it reports it to the proxy (we already have one special code 499 or 409 IIRC).

In such way, checking of constraints occurs where the best knowledge of constrains resides (in a specific back-end, as selected by SP). The biggest downside I see is that the same checking happens several times and returns the same error, so it's wasteful. Also, it involves network traffic, while this middleware doesn't. However, 1) isn't it an error condition that is not supposed to happen, so probably not happens often, and 2) other ways to sending erroneous requests that back-ends rejects may exist (maybe some timestamp things?).

Can we just sigh and ate the downsides of checking constraints in backends, where the natural knowledge of constraints is?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-18 04:27:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

This current change calls check_object_creation from Object controller only. We may need some checks during account and container creations as well. What do you think of a generic "validate_request" (better name?) method that could be defined and set in WSGI env by the custom middleware and then called inside proxy-server's handle_request method ? (This is also where swift.authorize method reference is called). 

IMO, this would add more flexibility in defining constraints for account and containers as well. For example, one can define a storage policy where container names do not exceed length X (or match a pattern).'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2014-08-19 19:17:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Sam, Thanks for your input. I want to make sure I understand your points, so I've got some questions. 

The check_object_creation method is called both in the proxy, but also in the PUT method of the object server, so I was expecting that it would _not_ be possible (or "advisible") to change configurations on an existing storage policy. It would be possible to GET an object, but I'd assume other operations such as replication could fail.

My other expectation is that a storage policy would not contain different DiskFile implementations, but only one. For example, I don't think one would create a replica-3 storage policy where a number of object servers are running the default core DiskFile and another number of object servers are running swiftonfile DiskFile. But even if that was the case, then it seems that providing a specific middleware for this storage policy makes sense so that you can have restrictions that intersect all the different diskfiles limitations in this storage policy.

Can you explain further the idea of having artification restrictions being per-storage-policy but being in core swift? It seems that if it is per-storage-policy, you can't necessarily have it be in core swift.


@Pete, When we first ran into this problem it was exactly because of the fact you described. Currently if the object servers returns an error (e.g., 400), the proxy just returns 503. So we could definetely fix that and it would in a way allow for having different constraints per storage policy. But then we still have the problem you describe of wasting network bandwidth by sending this requests to the object servers, just so they can return an error.


@Prashanth, I like the idea of also validating account and containers. I don't think we need to do all at once, but we can certainly work towards that.


For now, I plan on splitting this patch a bit. In a previous patch (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/111374/), we agreed to add some sanity checks on 'x-delete-at' and 'x-delete-after', which I ended up adding as part of this patch. I will now separate that work to simplify this patch and make it very specific about the primary topic.'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2014-08-19 19:19:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Wow, there is a lot of words in this comment thread, so I thought I'd add my thoughts. 

<! WARNING BRAIN DUMP INCOMING !>

So if I am paraphrasing correctly what Sam said/meant and alluded to by John is, there could be 2 different sets of constraints.

1. Artificial constraints, constraints that are required by the operators (ie, max file size for there cluster), but isn't really enforced on the object servers. [Sam's Firstly paragraph].
These should be in core swift, in swfit/common/constraints.py or with the storage policy (that is don't move all constraints there there own middleware). E.G. EC should have an artificial constraint specifying a minumum object size.

2. Other constraints could be global and be included via middlewares, allowing deployers/ops to specify there own constraints that aren't in swift core. These could include per DiskFile constraints so deployers/operators can insert them into the pipeline.

I don't mean to put words into Sam's mouth, but that was my understanding of his comments. I reworded/paraphrased his comment to extend it a little. While we are talking about custom constraints, maybe this is the time to unify what a constraint should be. Maybe we should create a Constraint object, which takes in a req and has a simple match function which returns a boolean:

  class Constraint(object):
      def match(self, req, **kargs):
          return True  

This way, swift can have a core set (constraints.py) and a new global method in SP objects like (get_constraints) whereby a bunch on constraints can be returned. This way constraints can be easily managed by the proxy. We could go one step further and add a constraintsMiddleware class which operators could simply inherit and override some simple method which can behave (to the ops/dev) identical to the get_constraints method in the SP. Doing the latter would lower the Dev experience/expertise required for ops to add there own custom global swift constraints to their clusters.

Anyway, that's my 2 cents.... a.k.a brain dump :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-12 06:24:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

[{'created': '2014-08-11 17:31:19.000000000', 'message': 'Storage Policy defined constraints middleware

Adding a constraints middleware that allows different
constraints rules per storage policy.

Currently, Swift allows only one set of object naming
and metadata rules per cluster. As new storage policies
are implemented, it is possible that different storage
back-ends have different set of rules on how objects
should be created for that specific storage system.

This patch attempts to refactor some of the default
object validation in PUT requests, so that the validation
happens early enough to quickly respond with errors, but
also adds the ability to new middlewares to define
their own constraints for a specific storage policy.

A mem_constraints middleware was added to serve as an

commit_message:
Storage Policy defined constraints middleware

Adding a constraints middleware that allows different
constraints rules per storage policy.

Currently, Swift allows only one set of object naming
and metadata rules per cluster. As new storage policies
are implemented, it is possible that different storage
back-ends have different set of rules on how objects
should be created for that specific storage system.

This patch attempts to refactor some of the default
object validation in PUT requests, so that the validation
happens early enough to quickly respond with errors, but
also adds the ability to new middlewares to define
their own constraints for a specific storage policy.

A mem_constraints middleware was added to serve as an
example where objects stored on an object mem_server
would have more strict naming rules (e.g., name length
max is 128).

A real-world example of where this constraints middleware
is necessary can be found on the SwiftOnFile project.
SwiftOnFile has different rules as objects name are mapped
to a POSIX filesystem directory structure.
Example: no names with double slashes or ending with
slashes are allowed.
SwiftOnFile constraints middleware: http://goo.gl/a96Icc

Change-Id: I46361969979c7ed9477f34cba9f74c13e89617d9
Signed-off-by: Thiago da Silva <thiago@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Moving data migration handling to base driver class

Experimenting with a new idea to move the handling
of the data migration to the base driver class.

This change introduces a new method migrate_object
and moves upload_object to DataMigrationDriver.

These changes allow for new drivers to override
upload_object and completely change the way data
is read from source and written to destination.
This new driver was created to test some new ideas
with the design of the migration middleware.

data_migration.py is now responsible for loading the
correct driver and calling its migrate_object method.

Change-Id: Ib7279d772f737f5b7e6832097e6d3c7393bdcf06
Signed-off-by: Thiago da Silva <thiago@redhat.com>

lines.

commit_message:
Add oslo module 'log' and its dependencies

Also added following oslo dependencies of the log module:
jsonutils,gettextutils,local,strutils,importutils,timeutils

Change-Id: I2c23d474ba410ba524778363af382f4c21b0ddc4

commit_message:
Safer use of eval

eval() was used with an empty globals parameter. This meant that
the expression could call __import__ and then do whatever (remove
all your files, for examples). By setting globals to
{'__builtins__': None} the expression can't use __import__.

This is for security hardening.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I91a32a62204dd44fa850f9ec0efd4f45cd3d72c2
Partial-Bug: #1367022

commit_message:
Add a server with volumes ResourceGroup example

Adds an example in response to a ML question, shows how you can
create a resource group containing a number of nested stacks containing
identical volumes and volume attachment resources, then pass in the
server ID to have the volumes attached to one server.

Also moves the current basic example into a resource_group subdirectory,
so we can collect related examples, and make more obvious that the
volume_with_attachment template is part of another example rather than
a standalone example template.

Change-Id: I1ffc1656286a981b6dc219038e03adbb8d5af775

commit_message:
require a minimum of websockify 0.6

Websockify 0.6 fixes a substantial number of zombie process issues
seen in Nova. It was released in Feb 2014, and all our current tests
in the gate have been with websockify 0.6. So this mostly brings g-r
in line with reality.

Change-Id: Ieb8945dbe4c3c4c3170ea5a53ca6370814c5e945
Closes-Bug: #1048703

commit_message:
lower the futures version to 2.1.2

Futures 2.1.2 is available in precise, so lowering the
required version makes it easier to deployers building
packages on that OS.

Change-Id: I59f05027063c22ff7f44fb12b22b0e8ad78ed0b0

commit_message:
VMware: do not cache image when root_gb is 0

Save space on datastore when the instance size has root_gb of
0. There is no need to cache the disk as it already exists on
the datastore.

TrivialFix

Closes-bug: #1304593
(cherry picked from commit 9b14ae62a6396a2599c8a2ada1a50e3f69a2eddc)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_driver_api.py
	nova/virt/vmwareapi/vmops.py

Change-Id: Iac75d97f40a1a91b8fa2df7fb4318fc2965fd93a

[{'created': '2014-09-11 18:24:40.000000000', 'message': 'Bump sqlalchemy-migrate to 0.9.2

The new version executes multi-statement SQL scripts statement by
statement. This is needed to pass some migration rules when using a
SQLAlchemy driver that does not support multiple statements passed to
.execute() as a single string (f.e. MySQL Connector).

One of the projects that rely on those multi-statement SQL scripts when
doing migrations is Glance.

blueprint enable-mysql-connector

Change-Id: I2b6779ace131d2a2431b5ab8c8fce8ab71dc2638
'}]
commit_message:
Bump sqlalchemy-migrate to 0.9.2

The new version executes multi-statement SQL scripts statement by
statement. This is needed to pass some migration rules when using a
SQLAlchemy driver that does not support multiple statements passed to
.execute() as a single string (f.e. MySQL Connector).

One of the projects that rely on those multi-statement SQL scripts when
doing migrations is Glance.

blueprint enable-mysql-connector

Change-Id: I2b6779ace131d2a2431b5ab8c8fce8ab71dc2638

commit_message:
Change order for yum-repos file in centos7 element

Due to changes in centos7 element to use package-installs the order
of yum-repos in pre-install.d needs to be changed, to make yum repos
available before package-installs is called to install packages.

Change-Id: I47b584506465d90247f30bad515a32323e52180e

commit_message:
Fix for missing notification in Sahara OSTF

Platform test for Sahara fails without any messages
if default security group doesn't have needed "TCP" rules.
Now needed "TCP" rules when running the test are created.

Closes-Bug: #1342639

Change-Id: I2e325252e12528b4f31241d903c6a4ef4e2965b3

commit_message:
Support custom nameservers in setup-neutron

Allow the network description to pass in the nameserver to be used
for the subnet, falling back to the default of 8.8.8.8 for floating
networks if one is not specified.

Change-Id: Ibd8a33b0f1a3e26fb14b5050dd7e536828a3f3eb

we need to set variable accordingly.

commit_message:
Set socket options in correct way

Currently socket options, socket.SO_REUSEADDR and socket.SO_KEEPALIVE
are set only if SSL is enabled.
The above socket options should be set no matter SSL is enabled or not.

Closes-Bug: #1369418

Change-Id: Ia5f6603918bda40be9965387bf464c581449d912

commit_message:
labs: dnsmasq config: /etc/hosts, DNS server, logging

Configure dnsmasq to use the Google Public DNS and the node VM's
/etc/hosts for resolving hostnames (lets instance VM resolve the names
of node VMs, e.g. ping controller-api).

This configuration is in effect as long as the instance VMs use dnsmasq
for DNS name resolution (they do not if the neutron subnet has
dns_nameservers configured).

Since we turn on verbose logging in neutron scripts on the network node
VM, enable logging for dnsmasq, too.

Change-Id: I4bf470ddd87034fc0dcf29b612860ccda057f5e0

commit_message:
Mark openstack-doc-tools as being a universal wheel

Universal is used to identify pure-Python module(by bdist_wheel).
For these, it is sufficient to build a wheel with _any_ Python ABI
version and publish that to PyPI (by whatever means).

Change-Id: I83c09e2d2658280fd799675e9ef290841b2cd087

[{'created': '2014-09-22 14:53:17.000000000', 'message': 'labs: unregister clone VM disk, snapshots

Exporting via cloned VMs leaves the exported disks and snapshots
registered with VirtualBox (whether or not we pass a "--register" flag
to clonevm). Moving the exported VMs away or trying to export again to
the same location makes VirtualBox complain.

If we register the cloned VM upon creation and then unregister it
afterwards, we get at least rid of the snapshots and have only the
base disk left to unregister manually. This rather complicated method
is implemented here.

The export VMs have "-e" attached to their names, making them easier to
unregister here. They are also easy to recognize when imported into a
VirtualBox that already has node VMs using the original names.

Change-Id: I4532fd3152e705c3b35265359d7e6b0d5facd55e
'}]
commit_message:
labs: unregister clone VM disk, snapshots

Exporting via cloned VMs leaves the exported disks and snapshots
registered with VirtualBox (whether or not we pass a "--register" flag
to clonevm). Moving the exported VMs away or trying to export again to
the same location makes VirtualBox complain.

If we register the cloned VM upon creation and then unregister it
afterwards, we get at least rid of the snapshots and have only the
base disk left to unregister manually. This rather complicated method
is implemented here.

The export VMs have "-e" attached to their names, making them easier to
unregister here. They are also easy to recognize when imported into a
VirtualBox that already has node VMs using the original names.

Change-Id: I4532fd3152e705c3b35265359d7e6b0d5facd55e

commit_message:
Add -s option for neutron metering rules

While adding iptables rule, cidr is added as destination for both ingress
and egress directions. Modified code to add -s for egress and -d for ingress.

Closes-bug: 1310589

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/services/metering/drivers/test_iptables_driver.py

Change-Id: Id9ca10855e6527d4bec689f8f9bcd6f681221954
(cherry picked from commit 72e8b5dc5a5e36722327efca4c399f0321e9bbbb)

commit_message:
nova net-delete of associated network is not informative enough

Intially nova net-delete <Network ID> was raising an
"InternalServerError" in case the requested network to delete was associated to
any project.This error category “InternalServerError” is appropriate but the
error message description is not informative enough.

Now, when the command is not able to delete the requested network because
it is associated with a project, a message stating “network must be
disassociated from project <project-id> before delete” will be raised.
Updated the code to raise the new error message.

Closes-Bug: #1301373
Change-Id: I73cd6b1825061e5415983ca7caa8b9a0bcea8225

commit_message:
nova net-delete network is not informative enough

Intially nova net-delete <Network ID> was raising an
"InternalServerError" in case the requested network to
delete was associated to any project.This error category
“InternalServerError” is appropriate but the error
message description is not informative enough.

Now, when the command is not able to delete the requested
network because it is associated with a project, a message
stating “network must be disassociated from project
<project-id> before delete” will be raised. Updated the
code to raise the new error message.

Change-Id: I8838aeb14d24298859ae880c0cd3d037fae7c925
Closes-Bug: #1301373

commit_message:
nova net-delete network is not informative enough

Intially nova net-delete <Network ID> was raising an
"InternalServerError" in case the requested network to
delete was associated to any project.This error category
“InternalServerError” is appropriate but the error
message description is not informative enough.

Now, when the command is not able to delete the requested
network because it is associated with a project, a message
stating “network must be disassociated from project
<project-id> before delete” will be raised. Updated the
code to raise the new error message.

Change-Id: I6c6ef22626afc7e9f4f2f64b23fb41b25d0abca8
Closes-Bug: #1301373

commit_message:
Allow capabilities to be set on ironic nodes

Since Ide39f4a2796b169025bf0083e021166ae35f30f8, Ironic has been able to
pass nodes' capabilities to the nova scheduler to allow for more
flexible and precise scheduling of instances.  This patch allows devtest
to pass capabilities from nodes.json (if they are present) to the
'ironic node-update' command which is already used to set nodes'
cpu_arch, memory and disk. The capabilities have to be passed in a
separate file of flavor definitions, and the nodes themelves actually
refer to flavors.

This is a rewrite of I533336d193ee7bc46a7be79ff689f447aaf5770a after
register-nodes moved repo.

Part of bp targeted-node-deployment

Change-Id: I7c85cea3f680acdd1c9e8491d6ac707fc227b0b8

commit_message:
Making workflow endpoint able to upload multiple workflows

* Added WorkflowListSpec that represents a top level specification
  for uploading workflows (shouldn't be confused with WorkflowSpecList)
* Added workflow service that takes care of parsing, validating and
  creating multiple workflows from definition
* Added unit tests for workflow service
* Fixed workflow controller to work with multiple workflows on post/put
* Fixed workflow controller tests

Change-Id: I70a46a16e1970673fec0352091e4b610f320fbb8

commit_message:
Allow user-defined flavors on the undercloud

Currently a single flavor called "baremetal" is created on the
undercloud.  This patch allows a user to specify flavors in more detail
by providing a json file containing flavor descriptions.

Part of bp targeted-node-deployment

Change-Id: Ia4e695a3137c84d7270769a2fdb617f9e8f0c964

You got the commit message other way around, you added port 9191 and 9292 was already configured.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2014-08-13 14:27:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

hi, thanks for fixing this but it seems there is more to say about it and I'm not sure if we should merge it or not

I realized glance-api currently gets configured to use glance-registry on local-ipv4 and that is why it works without the patch. 

We could change the glance-api config to use the controllers VIP; that would require an additional listener in haproxy too.

Yet with glance V2 API the registry is served by a different class so we won't need to deploy the additional -registry daemon at all. More here https://blueprints.launchpad.net/glance/+spec/registry-db-driver

I wonder if it makes sense to move to using the VIP or if we should leave things as they are now (so 9191 is not exposed) in light of recent updates."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2014-08-14 20:28:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-18 13:31:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
For Glance add port 9191 to the iptables list

Recent changes to enable security through iptables now
requires this.  Port 9292 was already being correctly configured.

Reference https://bugs.launchpad.net/tripleo/+bug/1356040

Change-Id: I5f2214cd70b3ccc3d8aabce48927b9f5dda5d75b
Closes-Bug: 1356040

commit_message:
Use auth_token from keystonemiddleware

This changes swift proxy-server conf to use the
keystone authtoken middleware from the
keystonemiddleware project. auth_token in
keystoneclient has been deprecated.

The corresponding change was made to swift in this patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109047/

Change-Id: I58dad8e1151067bf8df37e511fff5fc0e3dfb487

Link to volumes_dir

Packaged cinder uses a different /etc/cinder/volumes to the cinder
default volumes_dir.
